{"title_page": "KANVA Architecture", "text_new": "'''KANVA Architecture''' is a multidisciplinary collective specializing in architectural, construction and management needs with the ability to design at various scales and typologies. The Montreal based firm was founded in 2003 by Tudor Radulescu and Rami Bebawi.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://raic.org/awards/emerging-architectural-practice-award-%E2%80%94-2015-recipient|title=RAIC Emerging Architectural Practice Award \u2013 2015 Recipient|last=|first=|date=|website=raic.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Both Radulescu and Bebawi graduated from [[McGill University]]\u2019s [[McGill School of Architecture|School of Architecture]] in 2001 and shared an interest in balancing design with artistic expression and education.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metalocus.es/en/news/kanva-receives-2015-raic-emerging-architectural-practice-award|title=KANVA RECEIVES THE 2015 RAIC EMERGING ARCHITECTURAL PRACTICE AWARD|last=|first=|date=|website=cas.ryerson.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> Radulescu and Bebawi are respective mentors in the local architecture community, through regular participation as an invited guest critic for studio reviews and assisting graduate student in developing their thesis at [[McGill University]] and the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al|University of Montreal]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Both principals prioritize the ideology of reciprocal teaching, through allowing the students to influence their practice as much as they influence the development of student\u2019s architectural education.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe design firm makes a priority of bringing architecture into greater visibility for the general public. KANVA has initiated outreach programs to bring a wider audience to provide feedback for public projects, allowing users to become active participants within the design process.<ref name=\":0\" /> KANVA Architecture frames each design project as an experiment, allowing the practice to operate as an architectural incubator for innovative use of material experimentation and construction technology.<ref name=\":1\" /> This works well with their holistic design process which includes the development of custom one to one mock-ups before construction to lower the tolerance of error when assembling complex custom building components.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\nKANVA\u2019s design proposals have been featured in Canadian Architects, Azure, Architecture Movement Continuite, [[Dezeen]], [[ArchDaily]], [[Designboom]], Phaidon Atlas and The [[The New York Times|New York Times]].<ref name=\":1\" /> KANVA incorporates sustainable strategies in their work referring to adaptive reuse, material recycling, and healthy living through their experimental design process. KANVA in collaboration with [[NEUF architect(e)s]] won Canadian Institute of Steel Construction\u2019s Design Award for Excellence in Steel Construction in three out of the twelve categories in 2018.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/channels/news/kanva-and-neuf-architectes-win-three-cisc-awards-291811|title=KANVA and NEUF architect(e)s win three CISC awards|website=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> KANVA\u2019s proposal for the Saint-Hyacinthe Convention Centre won in the Commercial, Young Architects/Engineers and Jury Favorite categories.<ref name=\":2\" /> The innovative design firm are also recipients of the 2013 RAIC Award for Excellence, 2015 RAIC Emerging Practice Award, multiple Grands Prix du Design Awards and the [[Illuminating Engineering Society of North America|Illuminating Engineering Society]] Award. In 2018, KANVA\u2019s Imago proposal for Montreal, Canada won the Experimental \u2013 Future Projects\u2019 Awards at the [[World Architecture Festival]]. The proposal makes use of portable inflatable biomorphic structures to ignite a behavioral change within the circulation in Montreal\u2019s urban densities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/channels/news/kanvas-imago-project-lauded-world-architecture-festival-292338|title=KANVA\u2019s Imago project lauded at World Architecture Festival|website=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>\n\n== Design Projects ==\n\n=== The Edison Residence ===\nKANVA overlaps traditional construction techniques with digital mediums to maintain the integrity of the initial concept set forth. The Edison Residence was built in 2014 prioritizing the use of digital drawing tools and modelling mediums.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite thesis|title=Drawing on Context: Proposing a Hybrid Design Process for Textured Concrete|url=https://curve.carleton.ca/3a7bdece-6d3d-4a80-83bb-af72c575a8a2|publisher=Carleton University|date=2018|degree=Text|first=Johanna|last=Abril}}</ref> The Edison Residence is located north of McGill University\u2019s Milton Gates <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.e-architect.co.uk/montreal/edison-residence-in-montreal|title=Edison Residence in Montr\u00e9al|last=Solkoff|first=Joel|date=2016-11-13|website=e-architect|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and was built to house thirty student units with supporting amenities such as kitchen, living rooms and common areas.<ref name=\":3\" /> KANVA Architects uses digital tools to fabricate and cast varying movies frames sorted in a repetitive fashion along the fa\u00e7ade.<ref name=\":3\" /> The frames of the movie were chosen from Thomas Edison\u2019s ''Montreal Fire Department on Runners'' due to the scene\u2019s affinity towards the site\u2019s tragic past. The previous development on the site was a 19th century stone house which was later torn down due to significant damages caused by a fire. The tragedy surrounding the initial proposals demolition became the primary driver of the urban renewal project.<ref name=\":4\" /> The designers decided to develop a photoengraved concrete fa\u00e7ade system that enables the building envelope to tell a story. The project displays an architectural \u2018parlante\u2019 which is an \u201carchitecture that heightens the intellectual and perceptual experience of its inhabitants by stimulating active looking\u201d.<ref name=\":4\" /> The material palette was restrained to masonry due to the site being located within Montreal\u2019s Heritage Zone. However, the designers at KANVA did not see this a constraint but rather an opportunity in exploring the limited conventions surrounding concrete. The use of photoengraved concrete panels allowed for the user to re-imagine the story through varying forms of circulations, however the subtlety of engraving doe not overwhelm the users, rather acts as an invitation in exploring the story.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== El\u00e4\u00e4 Project ===\nKANVA\u2019s El\u00e4\u00e4 project was designed with the experimental theme of reforming the traditional multi-unit typology into a more responsive typology.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/it-takes-a-village-elaa-montreal-quebec/|title=It Takes a Village: El\u00e4\u00e4, Montreal, Quebec|date=2019-04-05|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> The project was built in 2019, located within the borough of [[Verdun, Quebec|Verdun]], which sits between the [[Saint Lawrence River|St. Lawrence River]] and the historic [[Lachine Canal]]. Verdun has many pockets of greenery and nature in which pedestrians make full use of. KANVA wished to continue and amplify the surrounding conditions of the site by proposing a village typology over the conventional multi-unit typology.<ref name=\":5\" /> El\u00e4\u00e4 consists of six multi-storey blocks with a total of 41 condo units. The central green space between the unit blocks serves as a \u201cconnective tissue\u201d to build a higher degree of interaction and community between residents. The courtyard\u2019s path meanders and shifts around the dense configuration of the massing blocks to allow the occupants to acknowledge the urban oasis that the proposed village typology provides.<ref name=\":5\" /> Traditional triplexes required there to be a clear front and back, causing the units to be long and narrow. However, the El\u00e4\u00e4 opposes this condition by having an inside and outside rather than a front and back to allow for more comfortable unit proportions with greater daylight and visual connection to the urban context.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n<!--== Bibliography ==-->\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Architecture firms of Canada]]\n", "text_old": "'''KANVA Architecture''' is a multidisciplinary collective specializing in architectural, construction and management needs with the ability to design at various scales and typologies. The Montreal based firm was founded in 2003 by Tudor Radulescu and Rami Bebawi <ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://raic.org/awards/emerging-architectural-practice-award-%E2%80%94-2015-recipient|title=RAIC Emerging Architectural Practice Award \u2013 2015 Recipient|last=|first=|date=|website=raic.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>. Both Radulescu and Bebawi graduated from [[McGill University]]\u2019s [[McGill School of Architecture|School of Architecture]] in 2001 and shared an interest in balancing design with artistic expression and education <ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metalocus.es/en/news/kanva-receives-2015-raic-emerging-architectural-practice-award|title=KANVA RECEIVES THE 2015 RAIC EMERGING ARCHITECTURAL PRACTICE AWARD|last=|first=|date=|website=cas.ryerson.ca|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>. Radulescu and Bebawi are respective mentors in the local architecture community, through regular participation as an invited guest critic for studio reviews and assisting graduate student in developing their thesis at [[McGill University]] and the [[Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al|University of Montreal]] <ref name=\":1\" />. Both principals prioritize the ideology of reciprocal teaching, through allowing the students to influence their practice as much as they influence the development of student\u2019s architectural education <ref name=\":1\" />.\n\nThe design firm makes a priority of bringing architecture into greater visibility for the general public. KANVA has initiated outreach programs to bring a wider audience to provide feedback for public projects, allowing users to become active participants within the design process <ref name=\":0\" />. KANVA Architecture frames each design project as an experiment, allowing the practice to operate as an architectural incubator for innovative use of material experimentation and construction technology <ref name=\":1\" />. This works well with their holistic design process which includes the development of custom one to one mock-ups before construction to lower the tolerance of error when assembling complex custom building components <ref name=\":1\" />.\n\n<br />\n\n== Awards and Honors ==\nKANVA\u2019s design proposals have been featured in Canadian Architects, Azure, Architecture Movement Continuite, [[Dezeen]], [[ArchDaily]], [[Designboom]], Phaidon Atlas and The [[The New York Times|New York Times]] <ref name=\":1\" />. KANVA incorporates sustainable strategies in their work referring to adaptive reuse, material recycling, and healthy living through their experimental design process. KANVA in collaboration with [[NEUF architect(e)s]] won Canadian Institute of Steel Construction\u2019s Design Award for Excellence in Steel Construction in three out of the twelve categories in 2018 <ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/channels/news/kanva-and-neuf-architectes-win-three-cisc-awards-291811|title=KANVA and NEUF architect(e)s win three CISC awards|website=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>. KANVA\u2019s proposal for the Saint-Hyacinthe Convention Centre won in the Commercial, Young Architects/Engineers and Jury Favorite categories <ref name=\":2\" />. The innovative design firm are also recipients of the 2013 RAIC Award for Excellence, 2015 RAIC Emerging Practice Award, multiple Grands Prix du Design Awards and the [[Illuminating Engineering Society of North America|Illuminating Engineering Society]] Award. In 2018, KANVA\u2019s Imago proposal for Montreal, Canada won the Experimental \u2013 Future Projects\u2019 Awards at the [[World Architecture Festival]]. The proposal makes use of portable inflatable biomorphic structures to ignite a behavioral change within the circulation in Montreal\u2019s urban densities <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/channels/news/kanvas-imago-project-lauded-world-architecture-festival-292338|title=KANVA\u2019s Imago project lauded at World Architecture Festival|website=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|language=en|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>.\n\n<br />\n\n== Design Projects ==\n\n=== The Edison Residence ===\nKANVA overlaps traditional construction techniques with digital mediums to maintain the integrity of the initial concept set forth. The Edison Residence was built in 2014 prioritizing the use of digital drawing tools and modelling mediums <ref name=\":3\">{{Cite thesis|title=Drawing on Context: Proposing a Hybrid Design Process for Textured Concrete|url=https://curve.carleton.ca/3a7bdece-6d3d-4a80-83bb-af72c575a8a2|publisher=Carleton University|date=2018|degree=Text|first=Johanna|last=Abril}}</ref>. The Edison Residence is located north of McGill University\u2019s Milton Gates <ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.e-architect.co.uk/montreal/edison-residence-in-montreal|title=Edison Residence in Montr\u00e9al|last=Solkoff|first=Joel|date=2016-11-13|website=e-architect|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref> and was built to house thirty student units with supporting amenities such as kitchen, living rooms and common areas <ref name=\":3\" />. KANVA Architects uses digital tools to fabricate and cast varying movies frames sorted in a repetitive fashion along the fa\u00e7ade <ref name=\":3\" />. The frames of the movie were chosen from Thomas Edison\u2019s ''Montreal Fire Department on Runners'' due to the scene\u2019s affinity towards the site\u2019s tragic past. The previous development on the site was a 19<sup>th</sup> century stone house which was later torn down due to significant damages caused by a fire. The tragedy surrounding the initial proposals demolition became the primary driver of the urban renewal project <ref name=\":4\" />. The designers decided to develop a photoengraved concrete fa\u00e7ade system that enables the building envelope to tell a story. The project displays an architectural \u2018parlante\u2019 which is an \u201carchitecture that heightens the intellectual and perceptual experience of its inhabitants by stimulating active looking\u201d <ref name=\":4\" />. The material palette was restrained to masonry due to the site being located within Montreal\u2019s Heritage Zone. However, the designers at KANVA did not see this a constraint but rather an opportunity in exploring the limited conventions surrounding concrete. The use of photoengraved concrete panels allowed for the user to re-imagine the story through varying forms of circulations, however the subtlety of engraving doe not overwhelm the users, rather acts as an invitation in exploring the story <ref name=\":4\" />.\n\n=== El\u00e4\u00e4 Project ===\nKANVA\u2019s El\u00e4\u00e4 project was designed with the experimental theme of reforming the traditional multi-unit typology into a more responsive typology <ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.canadianarchitect.com/it-takes-a-village-elaa-montreal-quebec/|title=It Takes a Village: El\u00e4\u00e4, Montreal, Quebec|date=2019-04-05|website=Canadian Architect|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-25}}</ref>. The project was built in 2019, located within the borough of [[Verdun, Quebec|Verdun]], which sits between the [[Saint Lawrence River|St. Lawrence River]] and the historic [[Lachine Canal]]. Verdun has many pockets of greenery and nature in which pedestrians make full use of. KANVA wished to continue and amplify the surrounding conditions of the site by proposing a village typology over the conventional multi-unit typology <ref name=\":5\" />. El\u00e4\u00e4 consists of six multi-storey blocks with a total of 41 condo units. The central green space between the unit blocks serves as a \u201cconnective tissue\u201d to build a higher degree of interaction and community between residents. The courtyard\u2019s path meanders and shifts around the dense configuration of the massing blocks to allow the occupants to acknowledge the urban oasis that the proposed village typology provides <ref name=\":5\" />. Traditional triplexes required there to be a clear front and back, causing the units to be long and narrow. However, the El\u00e4\u00e4 opposes this condition by having an inside and outside rather than a front and back to allow for more comfortable unit proportions with greater daylight and visual connection to the urban context <ref name=\":5\" />.\n\n<br />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n\n\n[[Category:Architecture firms of Canada]]\n", "name_user": "G\u00fcnniX", "label": "safe", "comment": "Reflist; reference before punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KANVA_Architecture"}
{"title_page": "Eilvese", "text_new": "{{Infobox German location\n|type = Ortsteil\n|Town = [[Neustadt am R\u00fcbenberge]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|52|32|47|N|9|24|53|E|region:DE|display=inline,title}}\n|image_coa =\n|state=Lower Saxony\n|elevation=\n|area=16.59\n|population=1517\n|Stand=2016\n|postal_code=31535\n|area_code=05034\n|district = Hanover\n|image_photo=\n|image_caption=\n}}\n\n'''Eilvese''' is a borough of [[Neustadt am R\u00fcbenberge]] in the [[Hanover (district)|district of Hanover]], [[Lower Saxony]] in Germany. It had a population of 1517 in 2016.<ref name=\"Bahn\">{{cite web|title=Bahnhofskategorieliste 2017|publisher=DB Station&Service AG|url=http://www.deutschebahn.com/file/de/11878072/Gs7Kdpi6tX5QSBwML8Y7x60_3Ls/13266486/data/bahnhofskategorieliste_2017.pdf|url-status=dead|format=PDF; 343&nbsp;KB|accessdate=2017-02-14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215030221/http://www.deutschebahn.com/file/de/11878072/Gs7Kdpi6tX5QSBwML8Y7x60_3Ls/13266486/data/bahnhofskategorieliste_2017.pdf|archivedate=2017-02-15|date=2016-12-16}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nEilvese has a [[Eilvese railway station|railway station]] and is served by line S2 of the [[Hanover S-Bahn]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neustadt am R\u00fcbenberge]]\n[[Category:Villages in Lower Saxony]]\n\n{{Hanover-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox German location\n|type = Ortsteil\n|Town = [[Neustadt am R\u00fcbenberge]]\n|coordinates = {{coord|52|32|47|N|9|24|53|E|region:DE|display=inline,title}}\n|image_coa =\n|state=Lower Saxony\n|elevation=\n|H\u00f6he-bis=\n|H\u00f6he-Bezug=DE-NN\n|area=16.59\n|population=1517\n|Einwohner-Stand-Datum=2016\n|Eingemeindungsdatum=1974\n|postal_code=31535\n|Postleitzahl2=\n|area_code=05034\n|Vorwahl2=\n|Lagekarte=\n|Lagekarte-Beschreibung=\n|district = Hanover\n|image_photo=\n|image_caption=Location in the municipality of [[Neustadt am R\u00fcbenberge]]\n}}\n\n'''Eilvese''' is a borough of [[Neustadt am R\u00fcbenberge]] in the [[Hanover (district)|district of Hanover]], [[Lower Saxony]] in Germany. It had a population of 1517 in 2016.<ref name=\"Bahn\">{{cite web|title=Bahnhofskategorieliste 2017|publisher=DB Station&Service AG|url=http://www.deutschebahn.com/file/de/11878072/Gs7Kdpi6tX5QSBwML8Y7x60_3Ls/13266486/data/bahnhofskategorieliste_2017.pdf|url-status=dead|format=PDF; 343&nbsp;KB|accessdate=2017-02-14|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170215030221/http://www.deutschebahn.com/file/de/11878072/Gs7Kdpi6tX5QSBwML8Y7x60_3Ls/13266486/data/bahnhofskategorieliste_2017.pdf|archivedate=2017-02-15|date=2016-12-16}}</ref>\n\n==Transportation==\nEilvese has a [[Eilvese railway station|railway station]] and is served by line S2 of the [[Hanover S-Bahn]].\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Neustadt am R\u00fcbenberge]]\n[[Category:Villages in Lower Saxony]]\n\n{{Hanover-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Markussep", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eilvese"}
{"title_page": "Burwash", "text_new": "{{For|other uses of Burwash|Burwash (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n | official_name=Burwash\n | country=England\n | region=South East England\n | static_image_name=Burwashstreet.jpeg\n | static_image_caption=Burwash High Street\n | area_footnotes=<ref name=ESiF>{{cite web |url=http://www.eastsussexinfigures.org.uk/webview/ |title=East Sussex in Figures |accessdate=26 April 2008 |publisher=East Sussex County Council}}</ref>\n | area_total_km2 =30.1\n| population = 2,713\n| population_ref = (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11121504&c=Burwash&d=16&e=62&g=6421477&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1444144276468&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>\n  | population_density= {{convert|217|/sqmi|/km2|abbr=on}}\n | os_grid_reference=TQ675247\n | coordinates = {{coord|51.00|0.39|display=inline,title}}\n | post_town=ETCHINGHAM\n | postcode_area=TN\n | postcode_district=TN19\n | dial_code=01435\n | constituency_westminster=[[Bexhill and Battle (UK Parliament constituency)|Bexhill and Battle]]\n | london_distance={{convert|41|mi}} [[Boxing the compass|NNW]]\n | shire_district=[[Rother District|Rother]]\n | shire_county=[[East Sussex]]\n }}\n'''Burwash''', archaically known as '''Burghersh''', is a rural village and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[Rother District|Rother]] district of [[East Sussex]], England. Situated 15 miles (24&nbsp;km) inland from the port of [[Hastings]], it is located five miles (8&nbsp;km) south-west of [[Hurst Green, East Sussex|Hurst Green]], on the [[A265 road]], and on the River Dudwell, a tributary of the [[River Rother (Eastern)|River Rother]]. In an area steeped in history, some nine miles (14&nbsp;km) to the south-east lies [[Battle Abbey]] and eight miles (13&nbsp;km) to the east is [[Bodiam Castle]].\n\nIts main claim to fame is that for half of his life [[Rudyard Kipling]] (1865\u20131936) lived in the village at [[Bateman's]]. Kipling used the house's setting and the wider local area as the setting for many of his stories in ''[[Puck of Pook's Hill]]'' (1906) and the sequel ''[[Rewards and Fairies]]'' (1910), and there is a Kipling room at \"The Bear\" public house, one of two pubs located along Burwash High Street. Rudyard's son [[John Kipling]], died during the [[First World War]] and is named on the village memorial at the end of Bell Alley Lane. He was named after Rudyard's father, the artist [[John Lockwood Kipling]], (1837\u20131911), who provided illustrations for ''[[The Jungle Book]]''. A complete collection of Kipling's works, including ''[[Just So Stories]]'', ''[[Rewards and Fairies]]'', ''[[The Man Who Would Be King]]'' and ''[[Kim (novel)|Kim]]'', was published as the \"Burwash Edition\" (1941).\n\n==History==\nThe town developed as a trading place when King [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] authorised a weekly market in 1252. He also allowed a three-day [[fair]] in May.<ref name=\"BPC History\">{{cite web |title=History |url=https://burwashparish.org.uk/history/ |website=Welcome to Burwash |publisher=Burwash Parish Council |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n[[Smuggling]] took place in the 18th and 19th centuries, and several smugglers' graves can still be seen in the churchyard of St Bartholomew's.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} The main route connecting [[Heathfield, East Sussex|Heathfield]] and [[Hawkhurst]] was a [[toll-road]], through Burwash, and was a notorious spot for [[highwaymen]]. Burwash was one of the villages involved in the [[Wealden iron industry]], and there was a [[forge]] located at Burwash Weald, close to the site of the historic \"Wheel\" public house.<ref>Mees, K. 2010 {{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/2516481/Mees_K._2010._Documentary_and_literary_evidence_relating_to_Burwash_Forge_and_Wynhamford_Mill_East_Sussex._Wealden_Iron_2nd_Series_30_10-29 |title=Documentary and literary evidence relating to Burwash Forge and Wynhamford Mill, East Sussex|accessdate=7 April 2012|publisher=WIRG}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\nThe High Street has been designated a [[Conservation area]] by [[Rother District Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rother.gov.uk/index.cfm?articleid=1404 |title=Conservation Areas|accessdate=29 May 2008|publisher=Rother district council}}</ref> The intention is to preserve the character of the village by strictly controlling building within the area. Additionally, the buildings along the High Street have been given [[listed building]] status by [[English Heritage]], including a garden wall.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1044042 |accessdate=29 May 2008}}</ref> The [[Bateman's]] mansion, a fine example of [[Jacobean architecture]] formerly owned by Rudyard Kipling, is now a [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] property, open to the public. It can be found just outside the main village on the Burwash Weald and Common side, and is set within {{convert|33|acre|m2}} of the [[Sussex Weald]], and includes a working [[watermill]] and millpond, which connects to the River Dudwell. The location was used while shooting the film [[My Boy Jack (film)|My Boy Jack]] (2007), starring [[Daniel Radcliffe]]\n\nThere is a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] within the parish\u2014[[Dallington Forest]], an area of ancient woodland. Its interest lies in a nationally rare habitat as a result of a steep-sided stream flowing through the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.english-nature.org.uk/special/sssi/sssi_details.cfm?sssi_id=1002152 |title=Natural England \u2013 SSSI|accessdate=3 October 2008|publisher=English Nature}}</ref>\n\nBurwash is located within the [[High Weald Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].\n\n==Governance==\nThe lowest level of government is the Burwash parish council, which meets once a month. The parish council is responsible for local amenities such as the provision of litter bins, bus shelters and allotments. It also provides a voice into the district council meetings. The parish council comprises thirteen councillors with elections being held every four years.\n\nRother District council provides the next level of government with services such as refuse collection, planning consent, leisure amenities and council tax collection. Burwash lies within the Darwell ward, which provides two councillors.\n\nEast Sussex county council is the third tier of government, providing education, libraries and highway maintenance. Burwash falls within the Rother North West ward.\n\nThe UK Parliament constituency for Burwash is [[Bexhill and Battle (UK Parliament constituency)|Bexhill and Battle]], which has been represented by [[Huw Merriman]] since the 2015 general election.\n\n==Notable people==\n[[Cricket]]er [[Albert Relf]] (1874\u20131937) was born here, [[The Who]] frontman [[Roger Daltrey]] maintains a [[Holmshurst Manor]] country estate and Lakedown fishery near Burwash Common, [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], singer and founding member of rock band [[The Cure]] is a resident. As Kipling's main home, Batemans was host to many notable visitors including fellow author [[Henry Rider Haggard|Sir Henry Rider Haggard]] and Kipling's cousin [[Stanley Baldwin]], who was Britain's Prime Minister from 1935\u20131937. [[Kingsley Amis]] visited Batemans whilst preparing a tribute to Kipling (Amis' father was a resident of Burwash in the 1960s). Ex-Prime Minister [[James Callaghan]] lived just outside the village. ''[[Picture Post]]'' photographer [[Thurston Hopkins]] was educated at St Joseph's Salesian school in the village.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Burwash}}\n\n{{Rother}}\n{{East Sussex1}}\n\n{{Portal|East Sussex}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Rother District]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|other uses of Burwash|Burwash (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n | official_name=Burwash\n | country=England\n | region=South East England\n | static_image_name=Burwashstreet.jpeg\n | static_image_caption=Burwash High Street\n | area_footnotes=<ref name=ESiF>{{cite web |url=http://www.eastsussexinfigures.org.uk/webview/ |title=East Sussex in Figures |accessdate=26 April 2008 |publisher=East Sussex County Council}}</ref>\n | area_total_km2 =30.1\n| population = 2,713\n| population_ref = (2011)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11121504&c=Burwash&d=16&e=62&g=6421477&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1444144276468&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=6 October 2015}}</ref>\n  | population_density= {{convert|217|/sqmi|/km2|abbr=on}}\n | os_grid_reference=TQ675247\n | coordinates = {{coord|51.00|0.39|display=inline,title}}\n | post_town=ETCHINGHAM\n | postcode_area=TN\n | postcode_district=TN19\n | dial_code=01435\n | constituency_westminster=[[Bexhill and Battle (UK Parliament constituency)|Bexhill and Battle]]\n | london_distance={{convert|41|mi}} [[Boxing the compass|NNW]]\n | shire_district=[[Rother District|Rother]]\n | shire_county=[[East Sussex]]\n }}\n'''Burwash''', archaically known as '''Burghersh''', is a rural village and [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] in the [[Rother District|Rother]] district of [[East Sussex]], England. Situated 15 miles (24&nbsp;km) inland from the port of [[Hastings]], it is located five miles (8&nbsp;km) south-west of [[Hurst Green, East Sussex|Hurst Green]], on the [[A265 road]], and on the River Dudwell, a tributary of the [[River Rother (Eastern)|River Rother]]. In an area steeped in history, some nine miles (14&nbsp;km) to the south-east lies [[Battle Abbey]] and eight miles (13&nbsp;km) to the east is [[Bodiam Castle]].\n\nIts main claim to fame is that for half of his life [[Rudyard Kipling]] (1865\u20131936) lived in the village at [[Bateman's]]. Kipling used the house's setting and the wider local area as the setting for many of his stories in ''[[Puck of Pook's Hill]]'' (1906) and the sequel ''[[Rewards and Fairies]]'' (1910), and there is a Kipling room at \"The Bear\" public house, one of two pubs located along Burwash High Street. Rudyard's son [[John Kipling]], died during the [[First World War]] and is named on the village memorial at the end of Bell Alley Lane. He was named after Rudyard's father, the artist [[John Lockwood Kipling]], (1837\u20131911), who provided illustrations for ''[[The Jungle Book]]''. A complete collection of Kipling's works, including ''[[Just So Stories]]'', ''[[Rewards and Fairies]]'', ''[[The Man Who Would Be King]]'' and ''[[Kim (novel)|Kim]]'', was published as the \"Burwash Edition\" (1941).\n\n==History==\nThe town developed as a trading place when King [[Henry III of England|Henry III]] authorised a weekly market in 1252. He also allowed a three-day [[fair]] in May.<ref name=\"BPC History\">{{cite web |title=History |url=https://burwashparish.org.uk/history/ |website=Welcome to Burwash |publisher=Burwash Parish Council |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n[[Smuggling]] took place in the 18th and 19th centuries, and several smugglers' graves can still be seen in the churchyard of St Bartholomew's.{{Citation needed|date=May 2008}} The main route connecting [[Heathfield, East Sussex|Heathfield]] and [[Hawkhurst]] was a [[toll-road]], through Burwash, and was a notorious spot for [[highwaymen]]. Burwash was one of the villages involved in the [[Wealden iron industry]], and there was a [[forge]] located at Burwash Weald, close to the site of the historic \"Wheel\" public house.<ref>Mees, K. 2010 {{cite web |url=https://www.academia.edu/2516481/Mees_K._2010._Documentary_and_literary_evidence_relating_to_Burwash_Forge_and_Wynhamford_Mill_East_Sussex._Wealden_Iron_2nd_Series_30_10-29 |title=Documentary and literary evidence relating to Burwash Forge and Wynhamford Mill, East Sussex|accessdate=7 April 2012|publisher=WIRG}}</ref>\n\n==Landmarks==\nThe High Street has been designated a [[Conservation area]] by [[Rother District Council]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rother.gov.uk/index.cfm?articleid=1404 |title=Conservation Areas|accessdate=29 May 2008|publisher=Rother district council}}</ref> The intention is to preserve the character of the village by strictly controlling building within the area. Additionally, the buildings along the High Street have been given [[listed building]] status by [[English Heritage]], including a garden wall.<ref>{{NHLE |num=1044042 |accessdate=29 May 2008}}</ref> The [[Bateman's]] mansion, a fine example of [[Jacobean architecture]] formerly owned by Rudyard Kipling, is now a [[National Trust for Places of Historic Interest or Natural Beauty|National Trust]] property, open to the public. It can be found just outside the main village on the Burwash Weald and Common side, and is set within {{convert|33|acre|m2}} of the [[Sussex Weald]], and includes a working [[watermill]] and millpond, which connects to the River Dudwell. The location was used while shooting the film [[My Boy Jack (film)|My Boy Jack]] (2007), starring [[Daniel Radcliffe]]\n\nThere is a [[Site of Special Scientific Interest]] within the parish\u2014[[Dallington Forest]], an area of ancient woodland. Its interest lies in a nationally rare habitat as a result of a steep-sided stream flowing through the site.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.english-nature.org.uk/special/sssi/sssi_details.cfm?sssi_id=1002152 |title=Natural England \u2013 SSSI|accessdate=3 October 2008|publisher=English Nature}}</ref>\n\nBurwash is located within the [[High Weald Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty]].\n\n==Governance==\nThe lowest level of government is the Burwash parish council, which meets once a month. The parish council is responsible for local amenities such as the provision of litter bins, bus shelters and allotments. It also provides a voice into the district council meetings. The parish council comprises thirteen councillors with elections being held every four years.\n\nRother District council provides the next level of government with services such as refuse collection, planning consent, leisure amenities and council tax collection. Burwash lies within the Darwell ward, which provides two councillors.\n\nEast Sussex county council is the third tier of government, providing education, libraries and highway maintenance. Burwash falls within the Rother North West ward.\n\nThe UK Parliament constituency for Burwash is [[Bexhill and Battle (UK Parliament constituency)|Bexhill and Battle]]. [[Huw Merriman]] was elected in the 2015 election, and again in 2017.\n\nAt European level, Burwash is represented by the [[South East England (European Parliament constituency)|South East England constituency]], which holds ten seats in the [[European Parliament]].\n\n==Notable people==\n[[Cricket]]er [[Albert Relf]] (1874\u20131937) was born here, [[The Who]] frontman [[Roger Daltrey]] maintains a [[Holmshurst Manor]] country estate and Lakedown fishery near Burwash Common, [[Robert Smith (musician)|Robert Smith]], singer and founding member of rock band [[The Cure]] is a resident. As Kipling's main home, Batemans was host to many notable visitors including fellow author [[Henry Rider Haggard|Sir Henry Rider Haggard]] and Kipling's cousin [[Stanley Baldwin]], who was Britain's Prime Minister from 1935\u20131937. [[Kingsley Amis]] visited Batemans whilst preparing a tribute to Kipling (Amis' father was a resident of Burwash in the 1960s). Ex-Prime Minister [[James Callaghan]] lived just outside the village. ''[[Picture Post]]'' photographer [[Thurston Hopkins]] was educated at St Joseph's Salesian school in the village.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Burwash}}\n\n{{Rother}}\n{{East Sussex1}}\n\n{{Portal|East Sussex}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in East Sussex]]\n[[Category:Rother District]]\n", "name_user": "72", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGovernance:update", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Burwash"}
{"title_page": "Freydal", "text_new": "{{short description|16th century uncompleted illustrated prose work}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Freydal fol133.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|A scene from the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\u2019s ''Freydal'' Illuminated manuscript: Freydal jousts with Veit von Wolkenstein (fol.133)<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=177\u2013178}}</ref>]]\n'''''Freydal''''' is an uncompleted illustrated prose narrative commissioned by the [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor, Maximilian I]] in the early 16th century. It was intended to be a romantic allegorical account of Maximilian's own participation in a series of [[Tournament (medieval)|jousting tournaments]] in the guise of the tale's eponymous hero, Freydal. In the story, Freydal takes part in the tournaments to prove that he is worthy to marry a princess, who is a fictionalised representation of Maximilian's late wife, [[Mary of Burgundy]].\n\nThe text was never completed, although a manuscript draft is held by the [[Austrian National Library]]. 256 [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature paintings]] to accompany the text were created by court painters, and 255 are preserved in an [[illuminated manuscript]] \u2018tournament book\u2019 held by the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in [[Vienna]]. These miniatures vividly record the different types of jousts that were popular at the time as well as the [[Masquerade ball|court masquerades]], or \u2018mummeries\u2019, that took place at the end of the day after each tournament. It is the most extensive visual record of late medieval tournaments and court masquerades that exists.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Albrecht D\u00fcrer - Portrait of Maximilian I - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|Portrait of [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], 1519.]]\n[[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] and his father [[Frederick III, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick III]] were part of what was to become a long line of [[Holy Roman Emperors]] from the [[House of Habsburg]]. Maximilian was elected [[King of the Romans]] in 1486; upon his father's death in 1493 he succeeded to the throne of the Holy Roman Empire.<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=303}}</ref>\n\nDuring his reign, Maximilian commissioned a number of [[Renaissance humanism|humanist]] scholars and artists to assist him in completing a series of projects, in different art forms, intended to immortalize his life and deeds and those of his Habsburg ancestors.<ref name=\"Watanabe-O'Kelly94\">{{harvnb| Watanabe-O'Kelly|2000|p=94}}</ref> He referred to these projects as ''Gedechtnus'' (\"memorial\"),<ref name=\"Kleinschmidt162\">{{harvnb|Kleinschmidt|2008|p=162}}</ref> and included a series of stylised autobiographical works: ''Freydal'', the prose romance ''[[Weisskunig]]'', and the poem ''[[Theuerdank]]''.<ref name=\"Watanabe-O'Kelly94\"/>\n\n''Freydal'' and ''Theuerdank'' are closely linked and together give an allegorical account of the events leading to Maximilian's marriage to [[Mary of Burgundy]] in 1477.<ref name=moma120>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=120}}</ref> Mary died five years later, in 1482.<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=300}}</ref> In ''Freydal'', which is partly a tribute to Mary,<ref name=\"Clephan 1995 88\">{{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=88}}</ref> the eponymous hero pursues his fair lady by [[jousting]] in [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]].<ref name=Freeman>{{harvnb|Freeman|2019}}</ref> ''Theuerdank'' is effectively a sequel in which the hero overcomes dangers on the journey to his wedding.<ref name=moma120/> ''Freydal'' has a comedic tone which contrasts with ''Theuerdank'', which has more of the character of a tragedy.<ref name=McLaren/>\n\nThe theme of ''Freydal'' reflects Maximilian's lifelong enthusiasm for jousting. He attended his first tournament at the age of 14 and was captivated by its traditions and spectacle.<ref name=Freeman/> He staged many tournaments, including those to celebrate his wedding to Mary of Burgundy in 1477, his coronation as King of the Romans in 1486 and on the occasion of the [[First Congress of Vienna]] in 1515.<ref name=Freeman/> Maximilian was himself a participant in tournaments from 1485 until 1511, when he was in his 50s.<ref>{{harvnb|Anderson|2017|pp=104\u2013105}}</ref> His affinity for jousting contributed to his [[soubriquet]] the \u201clast knight\u201d.<ref name=Freeman/>\n[[File:Freydal fol164.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Post-tournament festivities: grotesque-style dancers or mummers dance a [[moresca]] while Freydal, in a mask and holding torches, looks on (''Freydal'' ms. fol.164, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref name=Locke123/>]]\n\n==Creation and history==\nMaximilian appears to have begun planning in 1502.<ref name=moma123>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=123}}</ref> The name ''Freydal'' was derived from ''Freyd-alb'', meaning \"white joyful young man\"<ref>{{harvnb|Strobl|1913|p=4}}</ref> In that year, he instructed his court taylor, Martin Trummer \"to have drawn in a book all those costumes as yet seen in mummeries organised by his majesty\".<ref name=moma123/> A \u201cmummery\u201d was a late medieval courtly [[Masquerade ball|masquerade]] or costumed dance.<ref name=moma122>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=122}}</ref>\n\nThis developed into the commissioning of planning sketches for the entire work, created over the next ten years.<ref name=moma123/> They were drawn in pen on [[laid paper]], using brown and black ink with watercolour over black chalk and leadpoint.<ref name=moma123/> A collection of 203 of these are housed in the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|pp=120, 123}}</ref> A small number of additional drawings are held at the [[British Museum]] and the [[Vatican Library]].<ref name=moma123/>\n\nMaximilian took a leading part in the creation of the work.<ref name=Clephan87>{{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=87}}</ref> His instructions on the subjects to be illustrated as well as corrections, in his own hand, of some of the proofs have survived. In 1511, Maximilian dictated some of the text to his secretary, Max Trytssaurwein,<ref name=Clephan87/> (or Marx Treitzsauerwein<ref>{{harvnb|Kleinschmidt|2008|p=178}}</ref>) and the following year wrote \"''Freydal'' is half conceived, the largest part of which we have made in Cologne\".<ref name=moma123/> The work was never completed,<ref name=Locke121>{{harvnb|Locke|2015|p=121}}</ref> however, and the text exists only in draft form.<ref name=moma121>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=121}}</ref> The manuscript text dictated to Treitzsauerwein, and corrected in Maximilian's hand, is held by the [[Austrian National Library]] in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=63}}</ref>\n[[File:German 16th Century, Freydal, The Book of Jousts and Tournament of Emperor Maximilian I - Combats on Horseback (Jousts)(Volume II), c. 1515, NGA 216067.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Planning sketch for ''Freydal'', National Gallery of Art, Washington]]\n\nAlthough the text was never finalised, 256 high quality [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniatures]]<ref name=moma121/> were created between 1512 and 1515 to illustrate the text.<ref name=moma120/> These were painted on paper in [[gouache]] with gold and silver highlights over pen, pencil and leadpoint<ref name=moma120/> by two dozen anonymous<ref name=McLaren>{{harvnb|McLaren|2019}}</ref> court artists under the direction of the imperial master-taylor.<ref name=Locke121/> All but one of the paintings are preserved in an [[illuminated manuscript]] \u2018tournament book\u2019 held by the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in Vienna.<ref name=moma120/> The remaining painting has been missing since at least 1600.<ref name=moma121/>\n\nIt was intended to print and publish the work with [[woodcut]] illustrations derived from the miniatures.<ref name=Locke121/> Although Maximilian never succeeded in doing this,<ref name=Locke121/> and the text remained only a draft, five of the illustrations were trial printed.<ref name=moma121/> These were from woodcuts made in about 1516 by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], albeit the cutting was somewhat rough. A sixth woodcut has been attributed to [[Lucas Cranach the Elder]].<ref name=Kurth36>{{harvnb|Kurth|1963|p=36}}</ref> One of the woodcut blocks has survived, and is held by the [[Kupferstichkabinett Berlin]].<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=129}}</ref>\n\nIn modern times, the Kunsthistorisches Museum illuminated manuscript tournament book has been published twice. A multi-volume edition, edited by [[Quirin von Leitner]] ([[:de:Quirin von Leitner|de]]), was published in Vienna in stages between 1880 and 1882.<ref name=Clephan87/><ref>{{harvnb|von Leitner|1880\u20131882}}</ref> In 2019, the German publisher, [[Taschen]], published the entire tournament book in a single volume, edited by Stefan Krause.<ref name=McLaren/><ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2019}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\n\n===Narrative===\nBased on the draft text preserved in the Austrian National Library,<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|pp=121, 122 note 2}}; {{harvnb|Silver|2002|pp=63\u201364}}</ref> the story is an account of a series of [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]] in which Freydal&nbsp;\u2013 a young knight and Maximilian's literary ''[[alter ego]]''&nbsp;\u2013 demonstrates his valour in combat in order to earn honour and fame<ref name=Silver64>{{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=64}}</ref> and to win the hand of a princess.<ref name=moma121/> Freydal is the son of a \u201cmighty prince\u201d and he is born with \u201cnoble virtue\u201d; his heraldic colours are white, red, and black, symbolising purity, fire, and bravery.<ref name=Silver64/>\n\n[[File:Freydal 01.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Freydal in a \u201cjoust of war\u201d (''Antzogen-Rennen'') with Wolfgang von F\u00fcrstenberg (''Freydal'' ms. fol.17, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=172,174}}</ref>]]\nThe narrative begins with three noble ladies asking Freydal to compete in the tournaments.<ref name=moma121/> A description of sixty-four tournaments follows in a ritualised and repetitive pattern.<ref name=Silver64/> Each is hosted by one of the finest courts in the land and comprises two different types of jousting; a foot combat; and a masquerade ball.<ref name=moma121/> Freydal competes in each tournament and almost always wins.<ref name=Clephan87/> Once all the tournaments are completed, Freydal receives a letter from one of the noble ladies who, it transpires, is a powerful queen; in the letter, she professes her love for him. The narrative ends with Freydal setting out to search for her, and ''Theuerdank'' then takes up the subsequent story.<ref name=moma121/>\n\nThe work reflects Maximilian's vanity, as exemplified by a poem which forms part of the draft text:<ref name=\"Clephan 1995 88\"/>{{Quotation|This did the gallant Freydal<br>In knightly deeds of fame<br>Thus rendering illustrious<br>The glories of his name.<br>His virtues and his goodness<br>Are manifest to all;<br>His many glorious triumphs<br>At tilt, at masks and ball...<br>His like will ne\u2019er be seen again.<ref>translation {{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=88, note 1}}</ref>}}\n\nHowever, the tournaments described are based on encounters Maximilian actually had. This is evidenced by a list of people involved in the story in the first seven [[Paper quire|quire]]s of the draft text, and who are known to have been actual courtiers.<ref name=Silver64/>\n\n===Illuminated manuscript tournament book===\n[[File:Freydal 02.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|left|Freydal in a \u201cjoust of war with flying and exploding shields\u201d (''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'') with Sigmund von Welsperg (''Freydal'' ms. fol. 29, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=175\u2013176}}</ref>]]\nThe miniatures in the tournament book manuscript illustrate the types of [[jousting]] popular at the time, both on horse and on foot.<ref name=McLaren/> Freydal features in each illustrated combat and his opponent is an historical figure with whom Maximilian actually jousted.<ref name=McLaren/> Each picture, in the lower margin, identifies the name of the opponent and the other courtiers depicted.<ref name=Locke123>{{harvnb|Locke|2015|p=123}}</ref> Other tournament books exist, but ''Freydal'' is the largest from the late Middle Ages<ref name=moma120/> and is considered the best executed; it is also the only one to show spectacular falls.<ref name=McLaren/>\n\nTwo types of joust, ''Rennen'' (or \u201cjousts of war\u201d where the lance has a sharpened tip<ref name= joust>{{harvnb|Jeep|2001|p=759}}; {{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=63}}</ref>) and ''Stechen'' (or \u201cjousts of peace\u201d where the lance has a blunted tip<ref name= joust/>) are depicted for each tournament.<ref name=Clephan87/><ref name=moma121/> Within these two broad groupings, eleven sub-types are shown.<ref name=moma121/> In the ''Welsches Gestecht'' (Italian joust of peace) a board separates the jousters so that they can ride more closely to each other and strike their opponent frontally with greater force. This results in a spectacular splintering of the lances. In the ''Scharfrennen'' (joust of war with flying shields) the shield is shown loosely fixed to the rider's breastplate, the aim being to dislodge it. In contrast, the objective of the ''Antzogenrennen'' is to unseat the opponent and his shield is fixed to his armour.<ref name=moma121/> The ''Feldrennen'' (or ''Kampfrennen'') jousts replicate skirmishes in war and the riders wear battlefield armour. The rarest type of joust depicted is the ''Kr\u00f6nlrennen'' where one rider wears the armour of a joust of peace but wields the lance of a joust of war and the other rider  has the opposite combination.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nOne of the most spectacular jousts depicted is the ''Bundrennen'' (joust of war with flying shields without [[bevors]])<ref name=moma121/> and its variation, ''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'' (joust of war with flying and exploding shields).<ref name=moma125>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=125}}</ref> In the ''Bundrennen'', the shield is held in place on the rider's breastplate with a complicated spring mechanism and when it is struck in the right place by the opponent it is ejected high into the air.<ref name=moma121/> The ''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'' increases the spectacle by attaching multiple triangular platelets to the shield which, when the shield is ejected, come loose and explode into the air like a firework display.<ref name=moma125/> Maximilian claimed to have invented this type of joust.<ref name=Freeman/> \n[[File:Freydal 05.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Foot combat between Freydal and Claude de Vaudry (''Freydal'' ms. fol. 39, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref name=moma120/>]]\nIn each of the tournaments, the participants are shown engaging in a foot combat. A variety of weapons are used, including [[Mace (bludgeon)|iron clubs]] (''Eisenkolben''), [[Flail (weapon)|flails]] (''Drischel''), swords (''Turnierschwert'')<ref name=krause179>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|p=179}}</ref> and daggers.<ref name=krause181>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|p=181}}</ref> The ''[[Melee (tournament)|m\u00eal\u00e9e]]'' is also shown in the manuscript.<ref name=Clephan87/>\n\nAfter each of the sixty-four tournaments is a scene depicting a [[moresca]] (a pantomime dance) or other post-tournament festivities with male courtiers, including the knights who had competed in the tournament, dressing up to dance in a variety of exotic costumes.<ref name=Locke121/> Known as \u2018mummeries\u2019, these were a regular feature of the evening entertainment after tournaments.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nThe male courtiers in the mummeries in the manuscript dress up, amongst other things, in costumes based on nationality or ethnicity, for example [[Ottoman Turks|Turkish]], [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] or [[Burgundian Netherlands|Burgundian]] costume, or as animals such as [[apes]] and creatures with bird's heads.<ref name=Locke121/> In one masquerade illustrated, the male participants engage in [[cross-dressing]] and wear women's gowns.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nIn each scene, all the men are dressed in the same costume and normally wear a mask. Women, however, are always shown wearing their usual court attire.<ref name=Locke121/> In each of these post-tournament pictures, Freydal appears carrying a torch and wearing a mask.<ref name=Locke121/> The ''Freydal'' illustrations constitute the most extensive pictorial record of these late medieval court masquerades.<ref name=moma122/>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = center\n | header = <br>Scenes from the Kunsthistorisches Museum ''Freydal'' illuminated manuscript\n | total_width = 725\n | image_style = border:none;\n | perrow = 3\n\n | image2 = Freydal KK5073.jpg\n | alt2 = Flying shields\n | caption2 = ''Scharfrennen''&nbsp;\u2013 joust of war with flying shields (fol.157)\n\n | image1 = Stechen gegen Graf Sigmund von Hardegk.jpg\n | alt1 = Stechen\n | caption1 = ''Stechen''&nbsp;\u2013 joust of peace, against Sigmund von Hardegk (fol.106)\n\n | image3 = Freydal fol14.jpg\n | alt3 = Italian\n | caption3 = ''Welsches Gestecht''&nbsp;\u2013 Italian joust of peace (fol.14)\n\n | image4 = Freydal fol156 Mummerei.jpg\n | alt4 = Mummery\n | caption4 = Mummery festivities (fol.156)\n\n | image6 = Masquerade, Freydal manuscript, folio 207.jpg\n | alt6 = Cross-dressing mummery \n | caption6 = Cross-dressing mummery (fol. 207)\n\n | image5 = Freydal fol083.jpg\n | alt5 = Flail\n | caption5 = Foot combat with flails against Wilhelm Auer von Herrenkirchen zu Neudorf (fol.83)<ref name=krause179/>\n\n}}\n==Significance==\nTournament books were a feature of late medieval and renaissance courtly culture and provide a graphic record of the jousting and it\u2019s rituals. Notable examples include [[Le Livre des tournois|''King Ren\u00e9's Tournament Book'']] and the tournament books of the [[Electors of Saxony]].<ref name=KrauseNGA>{{harvnb|Krause|2014-15}}</ref> However, the ''Freydal'' illuminated manuscript is considered the most important<ref name=KrauseNGA/> and precious<ref name=Clephan87/> of this genre.\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|60em}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://etheses.whiterose.ac.uk/18205/ |title= The Tournament and its Role in the Court Culture of Emperor Maximilian I (1459-1519) |first=Natalie|last=Anderson |date=2017 |publisher=University of Leeds White Rose eTheses|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Robert Coltman|last= Clephan|title=The Mediaeval Tournament|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aLzW7-TaSmYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Robert+Coltman+Clephan%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCiaPqpermAhWpSRUIHee3DRsQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=1995|orig-year=1919|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=978-0-486-28620-4|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite news |first=Laura|last=Freeman|title= The joy of jousting |url= https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/05/the-joy-of-jousting/ |newspaper=The Spectator |date= 4 May 2019 |accessdate=9 January 2020|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=John M. |last=Jeep|title=Medieval Germany: An Encyclopedia|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PzorDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9781351665407&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim1pnu3fbmAhWQY8AKHcxYB6cQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2001|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-66540-7|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Harald|last= Kleinschmidt|title=Ruling the Waves: Emperor Maximilian I, the Search for Islands and the Transformation of the European World Picture C. 1500|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vWEiAQAAIAAJ|date=2008|publisher=Antiquariaat Forum|isbn=978-90-6194-020-3|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.nga.gov/research/casva/research-projects/research-reports-archive/krause-2014-2015.html |title= Freydal, the Tournament Book of Emperor Maximilian I: The Washington Manuscript|first=Stefan |last= Krause |date=2014-15|publisher=National Gallery of Art, Washington D.C.|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Stefan|last=Krause|editor-first=Sabine|display-editors=etal |editor-last=Haag|chapter= Die ritterspiel als ritter Freydalb hat gethon aus ritterlichem gmute \u2013 Das Turnierbuch Freydal Kaiser Maximilians I. |chapter-url= https://www.academia.edu/14910953/Das_Turnierbuch_Freydal_Kaiser_Maximilians_I |title=Kaiser Maximilian I: der letzte Ritter und das h\u00f6fische Turnier|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=aSaRngEACAAJ|year=2014|publisher=Schnell & Steiner|isbn=978-3-7954-2842-6|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-first=Stefan |editor-last=Krause|title=Das Turnierbuch Kaiser Maximilians I.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=umw1vwEACAAJ|year=2019|publisher=Taschen|isbn=978-3-8365-7681-9|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Willi|last=Kurth|title=The Complete Woodcuts of Albrecht D\u00fcrer|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U-RXmsclHiAC&pg=PA36|date=1963|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=978-0-486-21097-1|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Ralph P. |last=Locke|title=Music and the Exotic from the Renaissance to Mozart|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Dk8QCAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false |date= 2015|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-01237-0|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite news |title= Freydal: the 16th-century comic that captures the thrill of jousting |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/what-to-read/freydal-16th-century-comic-captures-thrill-jousting/ |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date= 25 May 2019 |accessdate=4 January 2020|first= Iona|last=McLaren|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Larry|last=Silver|editor-first=Pia F.|editor-last= Cuneo|title=Artful Armies, Beautiful Battles: Art and Warfare in the Early Modern Europe|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7jBT4V3gtkwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9004115889&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiytYnq4fbmAhXUSsAKHYf_B_UQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |year=2002|chapter=Shining Armor: Emperor Maximilian, Chivalry and War|publisher=Brill|isbn=90-04-11588-9|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Joseph|last= Strobl|title=Studien \u00fcber die literarische T\u00e4tigkeit Kaiser Maximilian I.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5tsDwAAQBAJ|date=1913|publisher=Georg Reimer|isbn=978-3-11-148391-7|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.taschen.com/pages/en/catalogue/art/all/01184/facts.freydal_medieval_games_the_book_of_tournaments_of_emperor_maximilian_i.htm?ranMID=42784&ranEAID=hL3Qp0zRBOc&ranSiteID=hL3Qp0zRBOc-HKnVIgchCxGIascx0cyR6w |title= The Legendary Tales of Emperor Maximilian I|author=Taschen Catalogue |publisher=[[Taschen]]|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Terjanian|editor-first=Pierre|title=The Last Knight: The Art, Armor, and Ambition of Maximilian I|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X-anDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9781588396747&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7kubikevmAhWMgVwKHeOrBtQQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2019|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=978-1-58839-674-7|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Freydal. Des Kaisers Maximilian I. Turniere und Mummereien |editor-last= von Leitner|editor-first=Quirin |year=1880\u20131882|url= https://archive.org/details/gri_33125010764674/page/n1 |publisher= Holzhausen|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Helen|last= Watanabe-O'Kelly|title=The Cambridge History of German Literature|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=feweVgIYXM8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9780521785730&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXkZnytermAhVTolwKHTMiB8wQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2000|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-78573-0|ref= harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/details/gri_33125010764674/page/n1 ''Freydal. Des Kaisers Maximilian I. Turniere und Mummereien''] 1880-1882 edition (Q.von Leitner, ed.) from [[Internet Archive]]\n*[https://www.khm.at/en/learn/research/forschungsprojekte/kunsthistorische-projekte/freydal-das-turnierbuch-kaiser-maximilians-i-von-151215/ Kunsthistorisches Museum: ''Freydal'' \u2013 Das Turnierbuch Kaiser Maximilians I.] (in German)\n*[https://www.nga.gov/global-site-search-page.html?searchterm=Freydal National Gallery of Art, Washington D.C.: ''Freydal'' drawings]\n*[https://www.taschen.com/pages/en/catalogue/art/all/01184/facts.freydal_medieval_games_the_book_of_tournaments_of_emperor_maximilian_i.htm?ranMID=42784&ranEAID=hL3Qp0zRBOc&ranSiteID=hL3Qp0zRBOc-HKnVIgchCxGIascx0cyR6w Freydal. Medieval Games. The Book of Tournaments of Emperor Maximilian I], [[Taschen]] Catalogue (in English)\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Literature of the German Renaissance]]\n[[Category:16th-century books]]\n[[Category:16th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Medieval tournament]]\n[[Category:Miniature painting]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|16th century uncompleted illustrated prose work}}\n{{Italic title}}\n[[File:Freydal fol133.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|A scene from the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\u2019s ''Freydal'' Illuminated manuscript: Freydal jousts with Veit von Wolkenstein (fol.133)<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=177\u2013178}}</ref>]]\n'''''Freydal''''' is an uncompleted illustrated prose narrative commissioned by the [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Holy Roman Emperor, Maximilian I]] in the early 16th century. It was intended to be a romantic allegorical account of Maximilian's own participation in a series of [[Tournament (medieval)|jousting tournaments]] in the guise of the tale's eponymous hero, Freydal. In the story, Freydal takes part in the tournaments to prove that he is worthy to marry a princess, who is a fictionalised representation of Maximilian's late wife, [[Mary of Burgundy]].\n\nThe text was never completed, although a manuscript draft is held by the [[Austrian National Library]]. 256 [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniature paintings]] to accompany the text were created by court painters, and 255 are preserved in an [[illuminated manuscript]] \u2018tournament book\u2019 held by the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in [[Vienna]]. These miniatures vividly record the different types of jousts that were popular at the time as well as the [[Masquerade ball|court masquerades]], or \u2018mummeries\u2019, that took place at the end of the day after each tournament. It is the most extensive visual record of late medieval tournaments and court masquerades that exists.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Albrecht D\u00fcrer - Portrait of Maximilian I - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|Portrait of [[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], 1519.]]\n[[Maximilian I, Holy Roman Emperor|Maximilian I]] and his father [[Frederick III, Holy Roman Emperor|Frederick III]] were part of what was to become a long line of [[Holy Roman Emperors]] from the [[House of Habsburg]]. Maximilian was elected [[King of the Romans]] in 1486; upon his father's death in 1493 he succeeded to the throne of the Holy Roman Empire.<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=303}}</ref>\n\nDuring his reign, Maximilian commissioned a number of [[Renaissance humanism|humanist]] scholars and artists to assist him in completing a series of projects, in different art forms, intended to immortalize his life and deeds and those of his Habsburg ancestors.<ref name=\"Watanabe-O'Kelly94\">{{harvnb| Watanabe-O'Kelly|2000|p=94}}</ref> He referred to these projects as ''Gedechtnus'' (\"memorial\"),<ref name=\"Kleinschmidt162\">{{harvnb|Kleinschmidt|2008|p=162}}</ref> and included a series of stylised autobiographical works: ''Freydal'', the prose romance ''[[Weisskunig]]'', and the poem ''[[Theuerdank]]''.<ref name=\"Watanabe-O'Kelly94\"/>\n\n''Freydal'' and ''Theuerdank'' are closely linked and together give an allegorical account of the events leading to Maximilian's marriage to [[Mary of Burgundy]] in 1477.<ref name=moma120>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=120}}</ref> Mary died five years later, in 1482.<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=300}}</ref> In ''Freydal'', which is partly a tribute to Mary,<ref name=\"Clephan 1995 88\">{{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=88}}</ref> the eponymous hero pursues his fair lady by [[jousting]] in [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]].<ref name=Freeman>{{harvnb|Freeman|2019}}</ref> ''Theuerdank'' is effectively a sequel in which the hero overcomes dangers on the journey to his wedding.<ref name=moma120/> ''Freydal'' has a comedic tone which contrasts with ''Theuerdank'', which has more of the character of a tragedy.<ref name=McLaren/>\n\nThe theme of ''Freydal'' reflects Maximilian's lifelong enthusiasm for jousting. He attended his first tournament at the age of 14 and was captivated by its traditions and spectacle.<ref name=Freeman/> He staged many tournaments, including those to celebrate his wedding to Mary of Burgundy in 1477, his coronation as King of the Romans in 1486 and on the occasion of the [[First Congress of Vienna]] in 1515.<ref name=Freeman/> Maximilian was himself a participant in tournaments from 1485 until 1511, when he was in his 50s.<ref>{{harvnb|Anderson|2017|pp=104\u2013105}}</ref> His affinity for jousting contributed to his [[soubriquet]] the \u201clast knight\u201d.<ref name=Freeman/>\n[[File:Freydal fol164.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Post-tournament festivities: grotesque-style dancers or mummers dance a [[moresca]] while Freydal, in a mask and holding torches, looks on (''Freydal'' ms. fol.164, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref name=Locke123/>]]\n\n==Creation and history==\nMaximilian appears to have begun planning in 1502.<ref name=moma123>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=123}}</ref> The name ''Freydal'' was derived from ''Freyd-alb'', meaning \"white joyful young man\"<ref>{{harvnb|Strobl|1913|p=4}}</ref> In that year, he instructed his court taylor, Martin Trummer \"to have drawn in a book all those costumes as yet seen in mummeries organised by his majesty\".<ref name=moma123/> A \u201cmummery\u201d was a late medieval courtly [[Masquerade ball|masquerade]] or costumed dance.<ref name=moma122>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=122}}</ref>\n\nThis developed into the commissioning of planning sketches for the entire work, created over the next ten years.<ref name=moma123/> They were drawn in pen on [[laid paper]], using brown and black ink with watercolour over black chalk and leadpoint.<ref name=moma123/> A collection of 203 of these are housed in the [[National Gallery of Art]] in [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|pp=120, 123}}</ref> A small number of additional drawings are held at the [[British Museum]] and the [[Vatican Library]].<ref name=moma123/>\n\nMaximilian took a leading part in the creation of the work.<ref name=Clephan87>{{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=87}}</ref> His instructions on the subjects to be illustrated as well as corrections, in his own hand, of some of the proofs have survived. In 1511, Maximilian dictated some of the text to his secretary, Max Trytssaurwein,<ref name=Clephan87/> (or Marx Treitzsauerwein<ref>{{harvnb|Kleinschmidt|2008|p=178}}</ref>) and the following year wrote \"''Freydal'' is half conceived, the largest part of which we have made in Cologne\".<ref name=moma123/> The work was never completed,<ref name=Locke121>{{harvnb|Locke|2015|p=121}}</ref> however, and the text exists only in draft form.<ref name=moma121>{{harvnb| Terjanian |2019|p=121}}</ref> The manuscript text dictated to Treitzsauerwein, and corrected in Maximilian's hand, is held by the [[Austrian National Library]] in [[Vienna]].<ref>{{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=63}}</ref>\n[[File:German 16th Century, Freydal, The Book of Jousts and Tournament of Emperor Maximilian I - Combats on Horseback (Jousts)(Volume II), c. 1515, NGA 216067.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Planning sketch for ''Freydal'', National Gallery of Art, Washington]]\n\nAlthough the text was never finalised, 256 high quality [[Miniature (illuminated manuscript)|miniatures]]<ref name=moma121/> were created between 1512 and 1515 to illustrate the text.<ref name=moma120/> These were painted on paper in [[gouache]] with gold and silver highlights over pen, pencil and leadpoint<ref name=moma120/> by two dozen anonymous<ref name=McLaren>{{harvnb|McLaren|2019}}</ref> court artists under the direction of the imperial master-taylor.<ref name=Locke121/> All but one of the paintings are preserved in an [[illuminated manuscript]] \u2018tournament book\u2019 held by the [[Kunsthistorisches Museum]] in Vienna.<ref name=moma120/> The remaining painting has been missing since at least 1600.<ref name=moma121/>\n\nIt was intended to print and publish the work with [[woodcut]] illustrations derived from the miniatures.<ref name=Locke121/> Although Maximilian never succeeded in doing this,<ref name=Locke121/> and the text remained only a draft, five of the illustrations were trial printed.<ref name=moma121/> These were from woodcuts made in about 1516 by [[Albrecht D\u00fcrer]], albeit the cutting was somewhat rough. A sixth woodcut has been attributed to [[Lucas Cranach the Elder]].<ref name=Kurth36>{{harvnb|Kurth|1963|p=36}}</ref> One of the woodcut blocks has survived, and is held by the [[Kupferstichkabinett Berlin]].<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=129}}</ref>\n\nIn modern times, the Kunsthistorisches Museum illuminated manuscript tournament book has been published twice. A multi-volume edition, edited by [[Quirin von Leitner]] ([[:de:Quirin von Leitner|de]]), was published in Vienna in stages between 1880 and 1882.<ref name=Clephan87/><ref>{{harvnb|von Leitner|1880\u20131882}}</ref> In 2019, the German publisher, [[Taschen]], published the entire tournament book in a single volume, edited by Stefan Krause.<ref name=McLaren/><ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2019}}</ref>\n\n==Content==\n\n===Narrative===\nBased on the draft text preserved in the Austrian National Library,<ref>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|pp=121, 122 note 2}}; {{harvnb|Silver|2002|pp=63\u201364}}</ref> the story is an account of a series of [[Tournament (medieval)|tournaments]] in which Freydal&nbsp;\u2013 a young knight and Maximilian's literary ''[[alter ego]]''&nbsp;\u2013 demonstrates his valour in combat in order to earn honour and fame<ref name=Silver64>{{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=64}}</ref> and to win the hand of a princess.<ref name=moma121/> Freydal is the son of a \u201cmighty prince\u201d and he is born with \u201cnoble virtue\u201d; his heraldic colours are white, red, and black, symbolising purity, fire, and bravery.<ref name=Silver64/>\n\n[[File:Freydal 01.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Freydal in a \u201cjoust of war\u201d (''Antzogen-Rennen'') with Wolfgang von F\u00fcrstenberg (''Freydal'' ms. fol.17, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=172,174}}</ref>]]\nThe narrative begins with three noble ladies asking Freydal to compete in the tournaments.<ref name=moma121/> A description of sixty-four tournaments follows in a ritualised and repetitive pattern.<ref name=Silver64/> Each is hosted by one of the finest courts in the land and comprises two different types of jousting; a foot combat; and a masquerade ball.<ref name=moma121/> Freydal competes in each tournament and almost always wins.<ref name=Clephan87/> Once all the tournaments are completed, Freydal receives a letter from one of the noble ladies who, it transpires, is a powerful queen; in the letter, she professes her love for him. The narrative ends with Freydal setting out to search for her, and ''Theuerdank'' then takes up the subsequent story.<ref name=moma121/>\n\nThe work reflects Maximilian's vanity, as exemplified by a poem which forms part of the draft text:<ref name=\"Clephan 1995 88\"/>{{Quotation|This did the gallant Freydal<br>In knightly deeds of fame<br>Thus rendering illustrious<br>The glories of his name.<br>His virtues and his goodness<br>Are manifest to all;<br>His many glorious triumphs<br>At tilt, at masks and ball...<br>His like will ne\u2019er be seen again.<ref>translation {{harvnb|Clephan|1995|p=88, note 1}}</ref>}}\n\nHowever, the tournaments described are based on encounters Maximilian actually had. This is evidenced by a list of people involved in the story in the first seven [[Paper quire|quire]]s of the draft text, and who are known to have been actual courtiers.<ref name=Silver64/>\n\n===Illuminated manuscript tournament book===\n[[File:Freydal 02.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|left|Freydal in a \u201cjoust of war with flying and exploding shields\u201d (''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'') with Sigmund von Welsperg (''Freydal'' ms. fol. 29, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|pp=175\u2013176}}</ref>]]\nThe miniatures in the tournament book manuscript illustrate the types of [[jousting]] popular at the time, both on horse and on foot.<ref name=McLaren/> Freydal features in each illustrated combat and his opponent is an historical figure with whom Maximilian actually jousted.<ref name=McLaren/> Each picture, in the lower margin, identifies the name of the opponent and the other courtiers depicted.<ref name=Locke123>{{harvnb|Locke|2015|p=123}}</ref> Other tournament books exist, but ''Freydal'' is the largest from the late Middle Ages<ref name=moma120/> and is considered the best executed; it is also the only one to show spectacular falls.<ref name=McLaren/>\n\nTwo types of joust, ''Rennen'' (or \u201cjousts of war\u201d where the lance has a sharpened tip<ref name= joust>{{harvnb|Jeep|2001|p=759}}; {{harvnb|Silver|2002|p=63}}</ref>) and ''Stechen'' (or \u201cjousts of peace\u201d where the lance has a blunted tip<ref name= joust/>) are depicted for each tournament.<ref name=Clephan87/><ref name=moma121/> Within these two broad groupings, eleven sub-types are shown.<ref name=moma121/> In the ''Welsches Gestecht'' (Italian joust of peace) a board separates the jousters so that they can ride more closely to each other and strike their opponent frontally with greater force. This results in a spectacular splintering of the lances. In the ''Scharfrennen'' (joust of war with flying shields) the shield is shown loosely fixed to the rider's breastplate, the aim being to dislodge it. In contrast, the objective of the ''Antzogenrennen'' is to unseat the opponent and his shield is fixed to his armour.<ref name=moma121/> The ''Feldrennen'' (or ''Kampfrennen'') jousts replicate skirmishes in war and the riders wear battlefield armour. The rarest type of joust depicted is the ''Kr\u00f6nlrennen'' where one rider wears the armour of a joust of peace but wields the lance of a joust of war and the other rider  has the opposite combination.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nOne of the most spectacular jousts depicted is the ''Bundrennen'' (joust of war with flying shields without [[bevors]])<ref name=moma121/> and its variation, ''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'' (joust of war with flying and exploding shields).<ref name=moma125>{{harvnb|Terjanian|2019|p=125}}</ref> In the ''Bundrennen'', the shield is held in place on the rider's breastplate with a complicated spring mechanism and when it is struck in the right place by the opponent it is ejected high into the air.<ref name=moma121/> The ''Geschifttartschen-Rennen'' increases the spectacle by attaching multiple triangular platelets to the shield which, when the shield is ejected, come loose and explode into the air like a firework display.<ref name=moma125/> Maximilian claimed to have invented this type of joust.<ref name=Freeman/> \n[[File:Freydal 05.jpg|upright=1.2|thumb|right|Foot combat between Freydal and Claude de Vaudry (''Freydal'' ms. fol. 39, [[Kunsthistorisches Museum|KMW]])<ref name=moma120/>]]\nIn each of the tournaments, the participants are shown engaging in a foot combat. A variety of weapons are used, including [[Mace (bludgeon)|iron clubs]] (''Eisenkolben''), [[Flail (weapon)|flails]] (''Drischel''), swords (''Turnierschwert'')<ref name=krause179>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|p=179}}</ref> and daggers.<ref name=krause181>{{harvnb|Krause|2014|p=181}}</ref> The ''[[Melee (tournament)|m\u00eal\u00e9e]]'' is also shown in the manuscript.<ref name=Clephan87/>\n\nAfter each of the sixty-four tournaments is a scene depicting a [[moresca]] (a pantomime dance) or other post-tournament festivities with male courtiers, including the knights who had competed in the tournament, dressing up to dance in a variety of exotic costumes.<ref name=Locke121/> Known as \u2018mummeries\u2019, these were a regular feature of the evening entertainment after tournaments.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nThe male courtiers in the mummeries in the manuscript dress up, amongst other things, in costumes based on nationality or ethnicity, for example [[Ottoman Turks|Turkish]], [[Republic of Venice|Venetian]] or [[Burgundian Netherlands|Burgundian]] costume, or as animals such as [[apes]] and creatures with bird's heads.<ref name=Locke121/> In one masquerade illustrated, the male participants engage in [[cross-dressing]] and wear women's gowns.<ref name=moma122/>\n\nIn each scene, all the men are dressed in the same costume and normally wear a mask. Women, however, are always shown wearing their usual court attire.<ref name=Locke121/> In each of these post-tournament pictures, Freydal appears carrying a torch and wearing a mask.<ref name=Locke121/> The ''Freydal'' illustrations constitute the most extensive pictorial record of these late medieval court masquerades.<ref name=moma122/>\n\n{{multiple image\n | align = center\n | header = <br>Scenes from the Kunsthistorisches Museum ''Freydal'' illuminated manuscript\n | total_width = 725\n | image_style = border:none;\n | perrow = 3\n\n | image2 = Freydal KK5073.jpg\n | alt2 = Flying shields\n | caption2 = ''Scharfrennen''&nbsp;\u2013 joust of war with flying shields (fol.157)\n\n | image1 = Stechen gegen Graf Sigmund von Hardegk.jpg\n | alt1 = Stechen\n | caption1 = ''Stechen''&nbsp;\u2013 joust of peace, against Sigmund von Hardegk (fol.106)\n\n | image3 = Freydal fol14.jpg\n | alt3 = Italian\n | caption3 = ''Welsches Gestecht''&nbsp;\u2013 Italian joust of peace (fol.14)\n\n | image4 = Freydal fol156 Mummerei.jpg\n | alt4 = Mummery\n | caption4 = Mummery festivities (fol.156)\n\n | image6 = Masquerade, Freydal manuscript, folio 207.jpg\n | alt6 = Cross-dressing mummery \n | caption6 = Cross-dressing mummery (fol. 207)\n\n | image5 = Freydal fol083.jpg\n | alt5 = Flail\n | caption5 = Foot combat with flails against Wilhelm Auer von Herrenkirchen zu Neudorf (fol.83)<ref name=krause179/>\n\n}}\n==Significance==\nTournament books were a feature of late medieval and renaissance courtly culture and provide a graphic record of the jousting and it\u2019s rituals. Notable examples include [[Le Livre des tournois|''King Ren\u00e9's Tournament Book'']] and the tournament books of the [[Electors of Saxony]].<ref name=KrauseNGA>{{harvnb|Krause|2014-15}}</ref> However, the ''Freydal'' illuminated manuscript is considered the most important<ref name=KrauseNGA/> and precious of this genre.<ref name=Clephan87/>\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n{{refbegin|60em}}\n* {{cite web |url= http://etheses.whiterose.ac.uk/18205/ |title= The Tournament and its Role in the Court Culture of Emperor Maximilian I (1459-1519) |first=Natalie|last=Anderson |date=2017 |publisher=University of Leeds White Rose eTheses|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Robert Coltman|last= Clephan|title=The Mediaeval Tournament|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=aLzW7-TaSmYC&printsec=frontcover&dq=inauthor:%22Robert+Coltman+Clephan%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjCiaPqpermAhWpSRUIHee3DRsQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=1995|orig-year=1919|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=978-0-486-28620-4|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite news |first=Laura|last=Freeman|title= The joy of jousting |url= https://www.spectator.co.uk/2019/05/the-joy-of-jousting/ |newspaper=The Spectator |date= 4 May 2019 |accessdate=9 January 2020|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=John M. |last=Jeep|title=Medieval Germany: An Encyclopedia|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=PzorDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9781351665407&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwim