Freydal: the 16th-century comic that captures the thrill of jousting |url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/books/what-to-read/freydal-16th-century-comic-captures-thrill-jousting/ |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]]|date= 25 May 2019 |accessdate=4 January 2020|first= Iona|last=McLaren|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Larry|last=Silver|editor-first=Pia F.|editor-last= Cuneo|title=Artful Armies, Beautiful Battles: Art and Warfare in the Early Modern Europe|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=7jBT4V3gtkwC&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9004115889&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiytYnq4fbmAhXUSsAKHYf_B_UQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |year=2002|chapter=Shining Armor: Emperor Maximilian, Chivalry and War|publisher=Brill|isbn=90-04-11588-9|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Joseph|last= Strobl|title=Studien \u00fcber die literarische T\u00e4tigkeit Kaiser Maximilian I.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Z5tsDwAAQBAJ|date=1913|publisher=Georg Reimer|isbn=978-3-11-148391-7|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite web |url= https://www.taschen.com/pages/en/catalogue/art/all/01184/facts.freydal_medieval_games_the_book_of_tournaments_of_emperor_maximilian_i.htm?ranMID=42784&ranEAID=hL3Qp0zRBOc&ranSiteID=hL3Qp0zRBOc-HKnVIgchCxGIascx0cyR6w |title= The Legendary Tales of Emperor Maximilian I|author=Taschen Catalogue |publisher=[[Taschen]]|ref=harv}}\n* {{cite book|editor-last=Terjanian|editor-first=Pierre|title=The Last Knight: The Art, Armor, and Ambition of Maximilian I|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=X-anDwAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9781588396747&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7kubikevmAhWMgVwKHeOrBtQQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2019|publisher=Metropolitan Museum of Art|isbn=978-1-58839-674-7|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book |title= Freydal. Des Kaisers Maximilian I. Turniere und Mummereien |editor-last= von Leitner|editor-first=Quirin |year=1880\u20131882|url= https://archive.org/details/gri_33125010764674/page/n1 |publisher= Holzhausen|ref= harv}}\n* {{cite book|first=Helen|last= Watanabe-O'Kelly|title=The Cambridge History of German Literature|url= https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=feweVgIYXM8C&printsec=frontcover&dq=isbn:9780521785730&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXkZnytermAhVTolwKHTMiB8wQ6AEIKTAA#v=onepage&q&f=false |date=2000|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-78573-0|ref= harv}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://archive.org/details/gri_33125010764674/page/n1 ''Freydal. Des Kaisers Maximilian I. Turniere und Mummereien''] 1880-1882 edition (Q.von Leitner, ed.) from [[Internet Archive]]\n*[https://www.khm.at/en/learn/research/forschungsprojekte/kunsthistorische-projekte/freydal-das-turnierbuch-kaiser-maximilians-i-von-151215/ Kunsthistorisches Museum: ''Freydal'' \u2013 Das Turnierbuch Kaiser Maximilians I.] (in German)\n*[https://www.nga.gov/global-site-search-page.html?searchterm=Freydal National Gallery of Art, Washington D.C.: ''Freydal'' drawings]\n*[https://www.taschen.com/pages/en/catalogue/art/all/01184/facts.freydal_medieval_games_the_book_of_tournaments_of_emperor_maximilian_i.htm?ranMID=42784&ranEAID=hL3Qp0zRBOc&ranSiteID=hL3Qp0zRBOc-HKnVIgchCxGIascx0cyR6w Freydal. Medieval Games. The Book of Tournaments of Emperor Maximilian I], [[Taschen]] Catalogue (in English)\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Literature of the German Renaissance]]\n[[Category:16th-century books]]\n[[Category:16th-century illuminated manuscripts]]\n[[Category:Medieval tournament]]\n[[Category:Miniature painting]]\n[[Category:Paintings of the Kunsthistorisches Museum]]\n", "name_user": "DeCausa", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSignificance", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Freydal"}
{"title_page": "This Morning (TV programme)", "text_new": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|British daytime television programme}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = This Morning\n| show_name_2              = {{Plainlist|\n* ''This Morning with Phillip & Holly''\n* ''This Morning with Eamonn & Ruth''\n*  ''This Morning with Richard & Judy''\n}} <!--- DO NOT REMOVE RICHARD AND JUDY - THE SHOW IS NAMED THIS WHEN THEY PRESENT -->\n| image                    = This Morning TV Logo.png\n| genre                    = {{ubl|[[Entertainment]]|[[Lifestyle (sociology)|Lifestyle]]}}\n| creator                  = Diane Nelmes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/03/independentproductioncompanies.itv|title=Diane Nelmes joins Liberty Bell|first=Leigh|last=Holmwood|date=3 October 2008|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n| director                 = \n| presenter                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Holly Willoughby]]\n* [[Phillip Schofield]]\n* [[Ruth Langsford]]\n* [[Eamonn Holmes]]\n* [[Judy Finnigan]]\n* [[Richard Madeley]]\n}}<!--- only regular hosts here -->\n| theme_music_composer     = David Pringle\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = [[British English|English]]\n| num_series               = 30\n| executive_producer       = Emma Gormley\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Royal Albert Dock, Liverpool|Albert Dock]] {{small|(1988\u201396, 2013)}}\n* Studio 8, [[The London Studios]] {{small|(1996\u20132018)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhknYAHhlfN|title=South Bank Filming Location}}</ref>\n* Studio TC3, [[Television Centre, London|Television Centre]] {{small|(2018\u2013)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhmCFy9Aops|title=Television Centre Filming Location}}</ref>\n}}\n| editor                   = Martin Frizell\n| runtime                  = 1988-?: 90 minutes {{small|(inc. adverts)}} <br> ?-2019: 120 minutes {{small|(inc. adverts)}} <br> 2020-: 150 minutes {{small|(inc. adverts)}}\n| company                  = {{ubl|[[ITV Granada|Granada Television]] {{small|(1988\u20132009)}}|[[ITV Studios]] {{small|(2009\u2013)}}}}\n| network                  = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| picture_format           = {{ubl|[[576i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]) {{small|(1988\u20132015)}}|[[1080i]] ([[High-Definition Television|HDTV]]) {{small|(2015\u2013)}}}}\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|1988|10|03|df=y}}\n| last_aired               = present\n}}\n\n'''''This Morning''''' is a British [[daytime television]] programme that is broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in the [[United Kingdom]], presented by [[Phillip Schofield]] and [[Holly Willoughby]], and [[Ruth Langsford]] and [[Eamonn Holmes]]. The show airs live and features news, topical items, showbiz, style and beauty, home and garden, food, health, real life and other similar features.\n\nThe series was originally presented by [[Richard Madeley]] and [[Judy Finnigan]] for more than a decade after its launch. It is currently presented alternatively by [[Phillip Schofield]] and [[Holly Willoughby]], and [[Ruth Langsford]] and [[Eamonn Holmes]], and has aired on [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] since 3 October 1988, making it one of the longest running daytime programmes on British television.\n\n==History==\nIn 1988, [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] decided to create a live daytime morning programme to replace the weekday morning edition of [[CITV|Children's ITV]]. Five regional ITV companies made [[Television pilot|pilot shows]] to bid for the national contract:\n* [[Television South]] offered a show called ''Home Today'', hosted by Andy Craig and [[Fern Britton]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hassell |first=Katherine |url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/showbiz/432909/Funny-facts-about-This-Morning-as-it-celebrates-its-25th-birthday |title=Funny facts about ''This Morning'' as it celebrates its 25th birthday |work=Daily Express |date=3 October 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Thames Television]]\n* [[Yorkshire Television]]<ref>This Morning 25th Anniversary, broadcast on 3 October 2013. Richard and Judy interview. </ref>\n* [[ITV Tyne Tees|Tyne Tees Television]]\n* [[ITV Granada|Granada Television]] offered a show called ''This Morning'', and was awarded the national contract.\n\nThe first episode of ''This Morning'' aired at 10:40 am on 3 October 1988 and finished at 12:10 pm, live from the Granada studio inside the [[Royal Albert Dock, Liverpool|Albert Dock]] in [[Liverpool]]. An industry insider believed the idea would not work and would be pulled by Christmas 1988, but despite ''This Morning'' being launched with no publicity, its ratings quickly rose to a daily average of two million viewers.\n\nIn the first few series', the show's \"experts\" were weatherman [[Fred Talbot]], [[Advice column |agony aunt]] [[Denise Robertson]], medic [[Chris Steele (doctor)|Dr Chris Steele]], cook Susan Brookes, beauty presenter [[Liz Earle]], hair and make-up artists Andrew and Liz Collinge, and wine expert Charles Metcalfe. The theme tune was by David Pringle, who also wrote opening music for ''[[Wheel of Fortune (UK game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'', ''[[Fun House (UK game show)|Fun House]]'' and ''[[The Pyramid Game]]''.\n\nTo end the first series, in 1989, the show was presented via satellite from Disneyland, California. Produced by Granada's Field Producer, Brian Thomas, the set was built directly in front of 'Sleeping Beauty Castle', a first for Disney. The 'special' week achieved the highest daytime viewing audiences outside of a Royal Wedding.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nAs part of the show, weather presenter [[Fred Talbot]] used a floating map of the [[British Isles]] to report the forecast.<ref>{{cite web |last=Warwick |first=Dave |title=Fred Talbot |url=http://www.davewarwick.co.uk/dave_warwick_fred_talbot.htm |accessdate=10 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201111106/http://www.davewarwick.co.uk/dave_warwick_fred_talbot.htm |archivedate=1 December 2008  }}</ref> A clip of [[Mark Roberts (streaker)|Mark Roberts]], a prolific [[streaking|streaker]], running onto Talbot's weather map in 1995 is regularly shown on clip shows.<ref name=RJMem>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8125210.stm Richard and Judy's memorable moments] BBC News, 1 July 2009</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the show was moved to [[the London Studios]] on the grounds that it was difficult to get celebrity guests to travel from London to Liverpool.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Opinion: Alex Connock |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/comment/blogs/s/1301990_opinion_alex_connock |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref> In the summer of 2001, Madeley and Finnigan left ''This Morning'' to present [[Richard & Judy|their own series on Channel 4]].\n\nThe show proved newsworthy on several occasions. In 2001 ''This Morning'' covered new ground by showing a gay partnership celebration live,<ref name=RJMem/> and a 2008 interview with [[Kerry Katona]] slurring her words also attracted coverage.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/tvandradioblog/2008/oct/22/kerry-katona-this-morning Kerry Katona's This Morning appearance was a new TV low] guardian.co.uk, 22 October 2008</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132015===\n[[File:This Morning titles.png|thumb|220px|right|''This Morning'' titlecard used from 2009 to 2015]]\nITV relaunched ''This Morning'' in 2009 with a new set and with [[Holly Willoughby]] replacing [[Fern Britton]] as co-host, which saw ratings rise by 20%.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/03/02/itv-tops-daytime-viewing-figures-thanks-to-women-presenters-115875-22080100 ITV tops daytime viewing figures thanks to women presenters] Mirror, 2 March 2010</ref>\n\n''This Morning Cook In!'', an interactive cook event, began on 1 March 2010. Each week, five viewers and a celebrity guest cooked along, via Skype, with [[Gino D'Acampo]] or [[Phil Vickery (chef)|Phil Vickery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/lifestyle/thismorning/thismorningcookin/ |accessdate=20 March 2010 |title=This Morning Cook in! |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312023925/http://www.itv.com/lifestyle/thismorning/thismorningcookin/ |archivedate=12 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 20 March 2010, ''This Morning'' increased from five to seven shows a week, with two new one-hour shows broadcast on the weekends, where Schofield and Willoughby presented pre-recorded links in between compilations of the week's programming. The weekend editions were later{{When|date=September 2019}} dropped from the schedule.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8565784.stm|title=This Morning to air at weekends |date=13 March 2010|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe 'Hub' interactive segment was heavily featured from 2010 until 2014. Presenters included [[Jeff Brazier]] (2013\u201314), [[Jenni Falconer]] (2013\u201314), [[Stephen Mulhern]] (2011\u20132014) [[Rylan Clark]] (2013\u201314), [[Emma Willis]] (2012\u20132014), [[Coleen Nolan]] (2010\u20132012), Samanthi Jayawardena (2010\u20132012) and [[Matt Johnson (TV presenter)|Matt Johnson]] (2010\u20132013).<ref>[http://www.nma.co.uk/news/itv-expands-cross-platform-offering-for-this-morning/3017746.article ITV expands cross-platform offering for This Morning] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607142217/http://www.nma.co.uk/news/itv-expands-cross-platform-offering-for-this-morning/3017746.article# |date=7 June 2011 }} New Media Age, 2 September 2010</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/thismorning/the-hub/matt-johnson-best-moments |title=Matt's best moments; The Hub &#124; This Morning |publisher=Itv.com |accessdate=24 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107010806/http://www.itv.com/thismorning/the-hub/matt-johnson-best-moments |archive-date=7 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 August 2013, [[Carol Vorderman]] took her first steps towards a 2014 [[Guinness World Records|World Record]] attempt by doing a solo flight to 1,000 metres high, live on ''This Morning''. Reporter [[Jenni Falconer]] covered the occasion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/daredevil-carol-vorderman-begins-her-flying-countdown-live-tv-first |title=Daredevil Carol Vorderman begins her flying countdown in a live tv first &#124; presscentre |publisher=Itv.com |date=19 August 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 October 2013, ''This Morning'' celebrated its 25th anniversary. The programme was broadcast live from its original home at [[Royal Albert Dock, Liverpool|Albert Dock]] in [[Liverpool]] with presenters [[Phillip Schofield]], [[Eamonn Holmes]], [[Holly Willoughby]] and [[Ruth Langsford]] being joined by original presenters [[Richard Madeley]] and [[Judy Finnigan]]. Numerous historical clips of the show were aired, including [[Gene Pitney]]'s [[Gene Pitney#This Morning incident|miming gaffe from 1989]]. [[Keith Lemon]] presented the weather from the show's famous floating weather map, while [[Stephen Mulhern]] presented various items including 'The Hub Sub' (the 'Hub' on a submarine).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-packs/morning-turns-25#.UkMfKNI3tLc |title=This Morning turns 25 &#124; presscentre |publisher=Itv.com |date=24 September 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> There was speculation concerning whether [[Fern Britton]] would return for the 25th anniversary; however, it was confirmed eight days beforehand that she would not.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a518265/fern-britton-not-involved-in-this-morning-anniversary.html |title=Fern Britton not involved in 'This Morning' anniversary \u2013 TV News |publisher=Digital Spy |date=25 September 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132018===\n{{sources|section|date=February 2019}}\nOn 27 August 2015, ''This Morning'' broadcast the remaining weeks' shows from the [[South Bank]] due to the main studio having a revamp ready for the new series on 1 September. The new series had many changes including a brand new set, theme music, titles and the new logo being painted onto the outside of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/morning-returns-new-series-brand-new-look|title=This Morning returns for a new series with a brand new look|work=ITV Press Centre}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, it was announced that [[The London Studios]], where ''This Morning'' is filmed, were planned to close for large-scale redevelopment in early 2018, and that ''This Morning'' would be relocated to [[Television Centre, London|Television Centre]] during construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/london/2017-02-21/itv-to-build-new-headquarters-on-the-site-of-its-famous-south-bank-studios/|title=ITV to build new headquarters on the site of its famous South Bank studios}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/news/west-london-news/itv-moves-white-city-morning-13197684|title=Which top TV stars are coming to White City after ITV deal?|first=Goolistan|last=Cooper|date=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, at the start of the summer series, new titles were made to match Langsford and Holmes presenting the show. The titles were different from the usual design, showing a behind-the-scenes look from the doors to the studio, make-up props and room, clothing department and the art gallery with a view of the studio at fast speed with crew in the presenters' place. The show was also retitled ''This Morning with Eamonn and Ruth''. The regular series titles used since 2015 returned on 4 September, when Willoughby and Schofield returned to the show.\n\n===2018\u2013present===\nFrom 1 to 5 October 2018, ''This Morning'' celebrated 30 years on air. During the week, it broadcast a live wedding, a brief come-back of the classic weather map from Albert Dock (presented by [[Alison Hammond]]), special opening titles, a new app, a live studio audience, a special 30 years bus (with correspondents Lisa Snowdon and Ore Oduba), as well as special games and guests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/amp/entertainment-arts-45717629|title=This Morning: ITV show receives special Bafta on its 30th birthday|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> On 2 October, an ITV special aired, entitled ''This Morning: 30 Unforgettable Years''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.metro.co.uk/2018/09/27/the-apprentice-doctor-who-and-30-years-of-this-morning-our-top-shows-to-watch-in-october-7970941/|title=The Apprentice, Doctor Who and 30 years of This Morning: Our top shows to watch in October|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nFrom 6 January 2020, an extra 30 minutes was added onto the show, which sees the show start at the earlier time of 10:00am as part of a change up of the ITV Daytime schedule.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/11/12/morning-get-even-longer-itv-revamps-morning-schedule-11083364/|title=This Morning and Good Morning Britain to get even longer as ITV revamps morning schedule|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Presenters==\n''This Morning'' is currently hosted by [[Phillip Schofield]] and [[Holly Willoughby]], and [[Eamonn Holmes]] and [[Ruth Langsford]]. The main relief presenters consist of [[Rochelle Humes]], [[Rylan Clark-Neal]] and [[Josie Gibson]] and [[Alison Hammond]]. Other stand-in presenters include [[Amanda Holden]], [[Christine Lampard]], [[Emily Atack]], [[Dr Ranj Singh]], [[Vanessa Feltz]], [[Ben Shephard]], [[Jenni Falconer]], [[Matt Edmondson]] and [[Davina McCall]].<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/tearful-fern-britton-quits-this-morning-sofa-1751227.html Tearful Fern Britton quits This Morning sofa] The Independent, 17 July 2009</ref>\n\nFrom October 1988 to July 2001, ''This Morning'' was presented by husband and wife [[Richard Madeley]] and [[Judy Finnigan]]. However, from 1998 onwards, they hosted only the Monday to Thursday editions, with regular guest presenters hosting on Fridays: during the tenth series [[Caron Keating]] and Ross Kelly presided, and from series 11 in 1999 [[Fern Britton]] and [[John Leslie (television presenter)|John Leslie]] were regular presenters of the Friday show. When Madeley and Finnigan departed the show in 2001, they were replaced by [[Coleen Nolan]] and [[Twiggy]], with [[Fern Britton]] and John Leslie remaining on Fridays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/twiggy-and-coleen-nolan-join-this-morning/1180440.article|title=Twiggy and Coleen Nolan join This Morning|work=broadcastnow.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a3552/twiggy-to-front-this-morning.html|title=Twiggy to front This Morning|work=Digital Spy}}</ref> However, Nolan and Twiggy proved less popular with viewers: Twiggy was later axed, whilst Nolan presented until the end of 2001 with Leslie, and was subsequently replaced by Britton.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/oct/02/itv.broadcasting|title=ITV axes Twiggy|author=Jessica Hodgson|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nAfter John Leslie was caught up in [[Ulrika Jonsson]]'s rape scandal, his contract was terminated, and he was replaced by Phillip Schofield in 2002. Schofield developed an on-screen relationship with Fern Britton that was characterised by good humour and giggling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a8812/schofield-to-join-this-morning.html#~pn1j4GEysLsLPy|title=Schofield to join \"This Morning\"|work=Digital Spy}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Ruth Langsford, who had been a guest presenter since 1999, and Eamonn Holmes became main presenters.\n\nOn 26 March 2009, Fern Britton announced that she was to leave ''This Morning'', and would be replaced by [[Holly Willoughby]] on 14 September 2009. On 17 July 2009, Britton presented her final show after 10 years.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/>\n\nIt has been confirmed, in an episode of [[Loose Women]] and This Morning, that [[Ruth Langsford]] is the longest-serving presenter of This Morning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b8NEJXGamMM|title=Ruth and Eamonn Celebrate 30 Years of This Morning {{!}} Loose Women|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<gallery caption=\"Current main presenters gallery\" widths=\"198px\" heights=\"180px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile: Holly Willoughby (cropped).jpg |[[Holly Willoughby]] (2009\u2013)\nFile:Philip_Schofield (cropped).jpg|[[Phillip Schofield]] (2002\u2013)\nFile:Ruth_langsford.jpg|[[Ruth Langsford]] (1999\u2013)\nFile:Eamon Holmes (cropped).jpg|[[Eamonn Holmes]] (2006\u2013)\n</gallery>\n\n==Ratings==\nThe show usually scores around 1 million viewers a day, a high rating for the ITV daytime schedules (6am-6pm). On 3 October 2018, the show had one of its highest ratings, when 2.7 million viewers tuned in for its 30th anniversary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/four-screen-dashboard/|title=Four-screen dashboard|publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]]|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n\n==Studio==\n[[File:This Morning 2015 Studio exterior.jpeg|200px|thumbnail|right|The 2015 exterior design of former studio coinciding with the programme's revamp.]]\nPrior to April 2018, ''This Morning'' broadcast live from Studio 8 at [[The London Studios]] on the South Bank, which features large picture windows looking out over the River Thames.<ref>[http://www.londonstudios.co.uk/studios/studio-details/studio-8/ Studio 8] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120804143212/http://www.londonstudios.co.uk/studios/studio-details/studio-8/ |date=4 August 2012 }} The London Studios</ref> Coinciding with the programme's revamp, the outside of the studio was repainted with the new ''This Morning'' logo and branding.\n\nSince 16 April 2018, ''This Morning'' has been broadcast from Studio 3 of the newly renovated [[Television Centre, London|Television Centre]] run by [[BBC Studioworks]], along with the rest of [[ITV Daytime]], including ''[[Loose Women]]'', ''[[Lorraine (TV programme)|Lorraine]]'' and ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC TV Centre reborn as refurbished studios welcome host of shows|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/bbc-tv-centre-reborn-as-refurbished-studios-welcome-host-of-shows-a3624236.html|date=31 August 2017|accessdate=18 April 2018|work=Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\nIt was planned to move back to the studios in 2023, but in October 2018, ITV announced it was looking to sell the site and would continue with the current studios and offices longer term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/oct/09/sale-of-itvs-south-bank-studios-could-net-250m|title=ITV to sell South Bank studios|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=9 October 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n''This Morning'' has won the [[National Television Award]] for Best Daytime/Live Magazine Show for 17 years running, from 1998 to 2020.<ref>{{www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/live-nta-2020-full-winners-21379456</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Group !! Award !! Result\n|-\n| 1998 || rowspan=\"4\"|[[National Television Awards]] || rowspan=\"4\"|Most Popular Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 1999 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2000 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2001 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2003 || rowspan=\"2\"|[[TV Quick Awards]] || rowspan=\"2\" | Best Daytime Viewing || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2004 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| National Television Awards || Most Popular Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2010 || rowspan=\"2\"|TV Times Awards || rowspan=\"2\" | Favourite Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2011 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| National Television Awards  || Best Topical Magazine Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Craft BAFTA  || Digital Creativity || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2012 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Factual Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[TRIC Awards]] || Best TV Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Freesat Awards || Best Live Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Craft Awards]] || Best Interactive Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2013 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TRIC Awards || Best TV Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2014 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TRIC Awards || Best TV Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Transgender Awards || Best Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2015 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Transgender Awards || Best Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2016 || National Television Awards || Best Live Magazine Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[TV Choice|TV Choice Awards]] || Best Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Royal Television Society || Daytime Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Transgender Awards || Best Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2017 || National Television Awards || Best Live Magazine Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TRIC Awards || Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Diversity in Media Awards || TV Moment of the Year || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| TV Choice|TV Choice Awards || Best Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2018 || National Television Awards ||  Best Live Magazine Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TRIC Awards || Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TV Choice|TV Choice Awards || Best Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2019|| National Television Awards || Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TV Choice|TV Choice Awards || Best Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2020|| National Television Awards || Most Popular Live Magazine Show || {{Won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0181261|title=This Morning}}\n* {{itv.com|id=thismorning|title=''This Morning''}}\n* {{stv.tv|id=thismorning|title=''This Morning''}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:This Morning (Tv Series)}}\n[[Category:1980s British television series]]\n[[Category:1990s British television series]]\n[[Category:2000s British television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British television series]]\n[[Category:1988 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:ITV television programmes]]\n[[Category:Television programmes produced by Granada Television]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-pc|small=yes}}\n{{short description|British daytime television programme}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = This Morning\n| show_name_2              = {{Plainlist|\n* ''This Morning with Phillip & Holly''\n* ''This Morning with Eamonn & Ruth''\n*  This Morning with Richard & Judy\n}} <!--- DO NOT REMOVE RICHARD AND JUDY - THE SHOW IS NAMED THIS WHEN THEY PRESENT -->\n| image                    = This Morning TV Logo.png\n| genre                    = {{ubl|[[Entertainment]]|[[Lifestyle (sociology)|Lifestyle]]}}\n| creator                  = Diane Nelmes<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2008/oct/03/independentproductioncompanies.itv|title=Diane Nelmes joins Liberty Bell|first=Leigh|last=Holmwood|date=3 October 2008|via=The Guardian}}</ref>\n| director                 = \n| presenter                = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Holly Willoughby]]\n* [[Phillip Schofield]]\n* [[Ruth Langsford]]\n* [[Eamonn Holmes]]\n* [[Judy Finnigan]]\n* [[Richard Madeley]]\n}}<!--- only regular hosts here -->\n| theme_music_composer     = David Pringle\n| country                  = United Kingdom\n| language                 = [[British English|English]]\n| num_series               = 30\n| executive_producer       = Emma Gormley\n| location                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Royal Albert Dock, Liverpool|Albert Dock]] {{small|(1988\u201396, 2013)}}\n* Studio 8, [[The London Studios]] {{small|(1996\u20132018)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhknYAHhlfN|title=South Bank Filming Location}}</ref>\n* Studio TC3, [[Television Centre, London|Television Centre]] {{small|(2018\u2013)}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BhmCFy9Aops|title=Television Centre Filming Location}}</ref>\n}}\n| editor                   = Martin Frizell\n| runtime                  = 1988-?: 90 minutes {{small|(inc. adverts)}} <br> ?-2019: 120 minutes {{small|(inc. adverts)}} <br> 2020-: 150 minutes {{small|(inc. adverts)}}\n| company                  = {{ubl|[[ITV Granada|Granada Television]] {{small|(1988\u20132009)}}|[[ITV Studios]] {{small|(2009\u2013)}}}}\n| network                  = [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]\n| picture_format           = {{ubl|[[576i]] ([[Standard-definition television|SDTV]]) {{small|(1988\u20132015)}}|[[1080i]] ([[High-Definition Television|HDTV]]) {{small|(2015\u2013)}}}}\n| first_aired              = {{Start date|1988|10|03|df=y}}\n| last_aired               = present\n}}\n\n'''''This Morning''''' is a British [[daytime television]] programme that is broadcast on [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] in the [[United Kingdom]], presented by [[Phillip Schofield]] and [[Holly Willoughby]], and [[Ruth Langsford]] and [[Eamonn Holmes]]. The show airs live and features news, topical items, showbiz, style and beauty, home and garden, food, health, real life and other similar features.\n\nThe series was originally presented by [[Richard Madeley]] and [[Judy Finnigan]] for more than a decade after its launch. It is currently presented alternatively by [[Phillip Schofield]] and [[Holly Willoughby]], and [[Ruth Langsford]] and [[Eamonn Holmes]], and has aired on [[ITV (TV channel)|ITV]] since 3 October 1988, making it one of the longest running daytime programmes on British television.\n\n==History==\nIn 1988, [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] decided to create a live daytime morning programme to replace the weekday morning edition of [[CITV|Children's ITV]]. Five regional ITV companies made [[Television pilot|pilot shows]] to bid for the national contract:\n* [[Television South]] offered a show called ''Home Today'', hosted by Andy Craig and [[Fern Britton]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Hassell |first=Katherine |url=http://www.express.co.uk/news/showbiz/432909/Funny-facts-about-This-Morning-as-it-celebrates-its-25th-birthday |title=Funny facts about ''This Morning'' as it celebrates its 25th birthday |work=Daily Express |date=3 October 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n* [[Thames Television]]\n* [[Yorkshire Television]]<ref>This Morning 25th Anniversary, broadcast on 3 October 2013. Richard and Judy interview. </ref>\n* [[ITV Tyne Tees|Tyne Tees Television]]\n* [[ITV Granada|Granada Television]] offered a show called ''This Morning'', and was awarded the national contract.\n\nThe first episode of ''This Morning'' aired at 10:40 am on 3 October 1988 and finished at 12:10 pm, live from the Granada studio inside the [[Royal Albert Dock, Liverpool|Albert Dock]] in [[Liverpool]]. An industry insider believed the idea would not work and would be pulled by Christmas 1988, but despite ''This Morning'' being launched with no publicity, its ratings quickly rose to a daily average of two million viewers.\n\nIn the first few series', the show's \"experts\" were weatherman [[Fred Talbot]], [[Advice column |agony aunt]] [[Denise Robertson]], medic [[Chris Steele (doctor)|Dr Chris Steele]], cook Susan Brookes, beauty presenter [[Liz Earle]], hair and make-up artists Andrew and Liz Collinge, and wine expert Charles Metcalfe. The theme tune was by David Pringle, who also wrote opening music for ''[[Wheel of Fortune (UK game show)|Wheel of Fortune]]'', ''[[Fun House (UK game show)|Fun House]]'' and ''[[The Pyramid Game]]''.\n\nTo end the first series, in 1989, the show was presented via satellite from Disneyland, California. Produced by Granada's Field Producer, Brian Thomas, the set was built directly in front of 'Sleeping Beauty Castle', a first for Disney. The 'special' week achieved the highest daytime viewing audiences outside of a Royal Wedding.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nAs part of the show, weather presenter [[Fred Talbot]] used a floating map of the [[British Isles]] to report the forecast.<ref>{{cite web |last=Warwick |first=Dave |title=Fred Talbot |url=http://www.davewarwick.co.uk/dave_warwick_fred_talbot.htm |accessdate=10 October 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201111106/http://www.davewarwick.co.uk/dave_warwick_fred_talbot.htm |archivedate=1 December 2008  }}</ref> A clip of [[Mark Roberts (streaker)|Mark Roberts]], a prolific [[streaking|streaker]], running onto Talbot's weather map in 1995 is regularly shown on clip shows.<ref name=RJMem>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8125210.stm Richard and Judy's memorable moments] BBC News, 1 July 2009</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the show was moved to [[the London Studios]] on the grounds that it was difficult to get celebrity guests to travel from London to Liverpool.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Opinion: Alex Connock |url=http://menmedia.co.uk/manchestereveningnews/comment/blogs/s/1301990_opinion_alex_connock |newspaper=Manchester Evening News |date=16 July 2010 |accessdate=29 July 2011}}</ref> In the summer of 2001, Madeley and Finnigan left ''This Morning'' to present [[Richard & Judy|their own series on Channel 4]].\n\nThe show proved newsworthy on several occasions. In 2001 ''This Morning'' covered new ground by showing a gay partnership celebration live,<ref name=RJMem/> and a 2008 interview with [[Kerry Katona]] slurring her words also attracted coverage.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/culture/tvandradioblog/2008/oct/22/kerry-katona-this-morning Kerry Katona's This Morning appearance was a new TV low] guardian.co.uk, 22 October 2008</ref>\n\n===2009\u20132015===\n[[File:This Morning titles.png|thumb|220px|right|''This Morning'' titlecard used from 2009 to 2015]]\nITV relaunched ''This Morning'' in 2009 with a new set and with [[Holly Willoughby]] replacing [[Fern Britton]] as co-host, which saw ratings rise by 20%.<ref>[https://www.mirror.co.uk/celebs/news/2010/03/02/itv-tops-daytime-viewing-figures-thanks-to-women-presenters-115875-22080100 ITV tops daytime viewing figures thanks to women presenters] Mirror, 2 March 2010</ref>\n\n''This Morning Cook In!'', an interactive cook event, began on 1 March 2010. Each week, five viewers and a celebrity guest cooked along, via Skype, with [[Gino D'Acampo]] or [[Phil Vickery (chef)|Phil Vickery]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/lifestyle/thismorning/thismorningcookin/ |accessdate=20 March 2010 |title=This Morning Cook in! |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100312023925/http://www.itv.com/lifestyle/thismorning/thismorningcookin/ |archivedate=12 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nFrom 20 March 2010, ''This Morning'' increased from five to seven shows a week, with two new one-hour shows broadcast on the weekends, where Schofield and Willoughby presented pre-recorded links in between compilations of the week's programming. The weekend editions were later{{When|date=September 2019}} dropped from the schedule.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/8565784.stm|title=This Morning to air at weekends |date=13 March 2010|publisher=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe 'Hub' interactive segment was heavily featured from 2010 until 2014. Presenters included [[Jeff Brazier]] (2013\u201314), [[Jenni Falconer]] (2013\u201314), [[Stephen Mulhern]] (2011\u20132014) [[Rylan Clark]] (2013\u201314), [[Emma Willis]] (2012\u20132014), [[Coleen Nolan]] (2010\u20132012), Samanthi Jayawardena (2010\u20132012) and [[Matt Johnson (TV presenter)|Matt Johnson]] (2010\u20132013).<ref>[http://www.nma.co.uk/news/itv-expands-cross-platform-offering-for-this-morning/3017746.article ITV expands cross-platform offering for This Morning] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607142217/http://www.nma.co.uk/news/itv-expands-cross-platform-offering-for-this-morning/3017746.article# |date=7 June 2011 }} New Media Age, 2 September 2010</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.itv.com/thismorning/the-hub/matt-johnson-best-moments |title=Matt's best moments; The Hub &#124; This Morning |publisher=Itv.com |accessdate=24 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140107010806/http://www.itv.com/thismorning/the-hub/matt-johnson-best-moments |archive-date=7 January 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nOn 21 August 2013, [[Carol Vorderman]] took her first steps towards a 2014 [[Guinness World Records|World Record]] attempt by doing a solo flight to 1,000 metres high, live on ''This Morning''. Reporter [[Jenni Falconer]] covered the occasion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/daredevil-carol-vorderman-begins-her-flying-countdown-live-tv-first |title=Daredevil Carol Vorderman begins her flying countdown in a live tv first &#124; presscentre |publisher=Itv.com |date=19 August 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 3 October 2013, ''This Morning'' celebrated its 25th anniversary. The programme was broadcast live from its original home at [[Royal Albert Dock, Liverpool|Albert Dock]] in [[Liverpool]] with presenters [[Phillip Schofield]], [[Eamonn Holmes]], [[Holly Willoughby]] and [[Ruth Langsford]] being joined by original presenters [[Richard Madeley]] and [[Judy Finnigan]]. Numerous historical clips of the show were aired, including [[Gene Pitney]]'s [[Gene Pitney#This Morning incident|miming gaffe from 1989]]. [[Keith Lemon]] presented the weather from the show's famous floating weather map, while [[Stephen Mulhern]] presented various items including 'The Hub Sub' (the 'Hub' on a submarine).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-packs/morning-turns-25#.UkMfKNI3tLc |title=This Morning turns 25 &#124; presscentre |publisher=Itv.com |date=24 September 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref> There was speculation concerning whether [[Fern Britton]] would return for the 25th anniversary; however, it was confirmed eight days beforehand that she would not.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a518265/fern-britton-not-involved-in-this-morning-anniversary.html |title=Fern Britton not involved in 'This Morning' anniversary \u2013 TV News |publisher=Digital Spy |date=25 September 2013 |accessdate=24 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n===2015\u20132018===\n{{sources|section|date=February 2019}}\nOn 27 August 2015, ''This Morning'' broadcast the remaining weeks' shows from the [[South Bank]] due to the main studio having a revamp ready for the new series on 1 September. The new series had many changes including a brand new set, theme music, titles and the new logo being painted onto the outside of the building.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/presscentre/press-releases/morning-returns-new-series-brand-new-look|title=This Morning returns for a new series with a brand new look|work=ITV Press Centre}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2017, it was announced that [[The London Studios]], where ''This Morning'' is filmed, were planned to close for large-scale redevelopment in early 2018, and that ''This Morning'' would be relocated to [[Television Centre, London|Television Centre]] during construction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.itv.com/news/london/2017-02-21/itv-to-build-new-headquarters-on-the-site-of-its-famous-south-bank-studios/|title=ITV to build new headquarters on the site of its famous South Bank studios}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.getwestlondon.co.uk/news/west-london-news/itv-moves-white-city-morning-13197684|title=Which top TV stars are coming to White City after ITV deal?|first=Goolistan|last=Cooper|date=19 June 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, at the start of the summer series, new titles were made to match Langsford and Holmes presenting the show. The titles were different from the usual design, showing a behind-the-scenes look from the doors to the studio, make-up props and room, clothing department and the art gallery with a view of the studio at fast speed with crew in the presenters' place. The show was also retitled ''This Morning with Eamonn and Ruth''. The regular series titles used since 2015 returned on 4 September, when Willoughby and Schofield returned to the show.\n\n===2018\u2013present===\nFrom 1 to 5 October 2018, ''This Morning'' celebrated 30 years on air. During the week, it broadcast a live wedding, a brief come-back of the classic weather map from Albert Dock (presented by [[Alison Hammond]]), special opening titles, a new app, a live studio audience, a special 30 years bus (with correspondents Lisa Snowdon and Ore Oduba), as well as special games and guests.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/amp/entertainment-arts-45717629|title=This Morning: ITV show receives special Bafta on its 30th birthday|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> On 2 October, an ITV special aired, entitled ''This Morning: 30 Unforgettable Years''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.metro.co.uk/2018/09/27/the-apprentice-doctor-who-and-30-years-of-this-morning-our-top-shows-to-watch-in-october-7970941/|title=The Apprentice, Doctor Who and 30 years of This Morning: Our top shows to watch in October|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref> \n\nFrom 6 January 2020, an extra 30 minutes was added onto the show, which sees the show start at the earlier time of 10:00am as part of a change up of the ITV Daytime schedule.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://metro.co.uk/2019/11/12/morning-get-even-longer-itv-revamps-morning-schedule-11083364/|title=This Morning and Good Morning Britain to get even longer as ITV revamps morning schedule|work=[[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]]|access-date=14 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Presenters==\n''This Morning'' is currently hosted by [[Phillip Schofield]] and [[Holly Willoughby]], and [[Eamonn Holmes]] and [[Ruth Langsford]]. The main relief presenters consist of [[Rochelle Humes]], [[Rylan Clark-Neal]] and [[Josie Gibson]] and [[Alison Hammond]]. Other stand-in presenters include [[Amanda Holden]], [[Christine Lampard]], [[Emily Atack]], [[Dr Ranj Singh]], [[Vanessa Feltz]], [[Ben Shephard]], [[Jenni Falconer]], [[Matt Edmondson]] and [[Davina McCall]].<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/tearful-fern-britton-quits-this-morning-sofa-1751227.html Tearful Fern Britton quits This Morning sofa] The Independent, 17 July 2009</ref>\n\nFrom October 1988 to July 2001, ''This Morning'' was presented by husband and wife [[Richard Madeley]] and [[Judy Finnigan]]. However, from 1998 onwards, they hosted only the Monday to Thursday editions, with regular guest presenters hosting on Fridays: during the tenth series [[Caron Keating]] and Ross Kelly presided, and from series 11 in 1999 [[Fern Britton]] and [[John Leslie (television presenter)|John Leslie]] were regular presenters of the Friday show. When Madeley and Finnigan departed the show in 2001, they were replaced by [[Coleen Nolan]] and [[Twiggy]], with [[Fern Britton]] and John Leslie remaining on Fridays.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/twiggy-and-coleen-nolan-join-this-morning/1180440.article|title=Twiggy and Coleen Nolan join This Morning|work=broadcastnow.co.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a3552/twiggy-to-front-this-morning.html|title=Twiggy to front This Morning|work=Digital Spy}}</ref> However, Nolan and Twiggy proved less popular with viewers: Twiggy was later axed, whilst Nolan presented until the end of 2001 with Leslie, and was subsequently replaced by Britton.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2001/oct/02/itv.broadcasting|title=ITV axes Twiggy|author=Jessica Hodgson|work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nAfter John Leslie was caught up in [[Ulrika Jonsson]]'s rape scandal, his contract was terminated, and he was replaced by Phillip Schofield in 2002. Schofield developed an on-screen relationship with Fern Britton that was characterised by good humour and giggling.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/tv/news/a8812/schofield-to-join-this-morning.html#~pn1j4GEysLsLPy|title=Schofield to join \"This Morning\"|work=Digital Spy}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, Ruth Langsford, who had been a guest presenter since 1999, and Eamonn Holmes became main presenters.\n\nOn 26 March 2009, Fern Britton announced that she was to leave ''This Morning'', and would be replaced by [[Holly Willoughby]] on 14 September 2009. On 17 July 2009, Britton presented her final show after 10 years.<ref name=\"independent.co.uk\"/>\n\nIt has been confirmed, in an episode of [[Loose Women]] and This Morning, that [[Ruth Langsford]] is the longest-serving presenter of This Morning.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=b8NEJXGamMM|title=Ruth and Eamonn Celebrate 30 Years of This Morning {{!}} Loose Women|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n<gallery caption=\"Current main presenters gallery\" widths=\"198px\" heights=\"180px\" perrow=\"4\">\nFile: Holly Willoughby (cropped).jpg |[[Holly Willoughby]] (2009\u2013)\nFile:Philip_Schofield (cropped).jpg|[[Phillip Schofield]] (2002\u2013)\nFile:Ruth_langsford.jpg|[[Ruth Langsford]] (1999\u2013)\nFile:Eamon Holmes (cropped).jpg|[[Eamonn Holmes]] (2006\u2013)\n</gallery>\n\n==Ratings==\nThe show usually scores around 1 million viewers a day, a high rating for the ITV daytime schedules (6am-6pm). On 3 October 2018, the show had one of its highest ratings, when 2.7 million viewers tuned in for its 30th anniversary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.barb.co.uk/viewing-data/four-screen-dashboard/|title=Four-screen dashboard|publisher=[[Broadcasters' Audience Research Board]]|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-09-20}}</ref>\n\n==Studio==\n[[File:This Morning 2015 Studio exterior.jpeg|200px|thumbnail|right|The 2015 exterior design of former studio coinciding with the programme's revamp.]]\nPrior to April 2018, ''This Morning'' broadcast live from Studio 8 at [[The London Studios]] on the South Bank, which features large picture windows looking out over the River Thames.<ref>[http://www.londonstudios.co.uk/studios/studio-details/studio-8/ Studio 8] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20120804143212/http://www.londonstudios.co.uk/studios/studio-details/studio-8/ |date=4 August 2012 }} The London Studios</ref> Coinciding with the programme's revamp, the outside of the studio was repainted with the new ''This Morning'' logo and branding.\n\nSince 16 April 2018, ''This Morning'' has been broadcast from Studio 3 of the newly renovated [[Television Centre, London|Television Centre]] run by [[BBC Studioworks]], along with the rest of [[ITV Daytime]], including ''[[Loose Women]]'', ''[[Lorraine (TV programme)|Lorraine]]'' and ''[[Good Morning Britain (2014 TV programme)|Good Morning Britain]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC TV Centre reborn as refurbished studios welcome host of shows|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/stayingin/tvfilm/bbc-tv-centre-reborn-as-refurbished-studios-welcome-host-of-shows-a3624236.html|date=31 August 2017|accessdate=18 April 2018|work=Evening Standard}}</ref>\n\nIt was planned to move back to the studios in 2023, but in October 2018, ITV announced it was looking to sell the site and would continue with the current studios and offices longer term.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/business/2018/oct/09/sale-of-itvs-south-bank-studios-could-net-250m|title=ITV to sell South Bank studios|last=Sweney|first=Mark|date=9 October 2018|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=9 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n''This Morning'' has won the [[National Television Award]] for Best Daytime/Live Magazine Show for 17 years running, from 1998 to 2020.<ref>{{www.mirror.co.uk/tv/tv-news/live-nta-2020-full-winners-21379456</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Group !! Award !! Result\n|-\n| 1998 || rowspan=\"4\"|[[National Television Awards]] || rowspan=\"4\"|Most Popular Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 1999 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2000 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2001 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2003 || rowspan=\"2\"|[[TV Quick Awards]] || rowspan=\"2\" | Best Daytime Viewing || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2004 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| National Television Awards || Most Popular Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| 2010 || rowspan=\"2\"|TV Times Awards || rowspan=\"2\" | Favourite Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2011 || {{Won}}\n|-\n| National Television Awards  || Best Topical Magazine Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Craft BAFTA  || Digital Creativity || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2012 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Factual Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[TRIC Awards]] || Best TV Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Freesat Awards || Best Live Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[BAFTA Craft Awards]] || Best Interactive Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2013 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TRIC Awards || Best TV Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\"|2014 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TRIC Awards || Best TV Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Transgender Awards || Best Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\"|2015 || National Television Awards || Most Popular Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Transgender Awards || Best Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2016 || National Television Awards || Best Live Magazine Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| [[TV Choice|TV Choice Awards]] || Best Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Royal Television Society || Daytime Programme || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| Transgender Awards || Best Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2017 || National Television Awards || Best Live Magazine Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TRIC Awards || Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| Diversity in Media Awards || TV Moment of the Year || {{Nom}}\n|-\n| TV Choice|TV Choice Awards || Best Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2018 || National Television Awards ||  Best Live Magazine Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TRIC Awards || Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TV Choice|TV Choice Awards || Best Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2019|| National Television Awards || Daytime Programme || {{Won}}\n|-\n| TV Choice|TV Choice Awards || Best Daytime Show || {{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2020|| National Television Awards || Most Popular Live Magazine Show || {{Won}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=0181261|title=This Morning}}\n* {{itv.com|id=thismorning|title=''This Morning''}}\n* {{stv.tv|id=thismorning|title=''This Morning''}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:This Morning (Tv Series)}}\n[[Category:1980s British television series]]\n[[Category:1990s British television series]]\n[[Category:2000s British television series]]\n[[Category:2010s British television series]]\n[[Category:2020s British television series]]\n[[Category:1988 British television series debuts]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:ITV television programmes]]\n[[Category:Television programmes produced by Granada Television]]\n[[Category:Television series by ITV Studios]]\n", "name_user": "Felida97", "label": "safe", "comment": "italics for alternative title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/This_Morning_(TV_programme)"}
